(638, 'VOICES', '{subdued} For the Caliph. Haroun Al Raschid. ', '  For the Caliph. Haroun Al Raschid. ', '{subdued}'),
(639, 'BELLO', '{gaily} Right. Let them all come. The scanty, daringly short skirt, riding up at the knee to show a peep of white pantalette, is a potent weapon and transparent stockings, emeraldgartered, with the long straight seam trailing up beyond the knee, appeal to the better instincts of the blasé man about town. Learn the smooth mincing walk on four inch Louis Quinze heels, the Grecian bend with provoking croup, the thighs fluescent, knees modestly kissing. Bring all your powers of fascination to bear on them. Pander to their Gomorrahan vices. ', '  Right. Let them all come. The scanty, daringly short skirt, riding up at the knee to show a peep of white pantalette, is a potent weapon and transparent stockings, emeraldgartered, with the long straight seam trailing up beyond the knee, appeal to the better instincts of the blasé man about town. Learn the smooth mincing walk on four inch Louis Quinze heels, the Grecian bend with provoking croup, the thighs fluescent, knees modestly kissing. Bring all your powers of fascination to bear on them. Pander to their Gomorrahan vices. ', '{gaily}'),
(640, 'BLOOM', '{bends his blushing face into his armpit and simpers with forefinger in mouth} O, I know what you''re hinting at now! ', '  O, I know what you''re hinting at now! ', '{bends his blushing face into his armpit and simpers with forefinger in mouth}'),
(641, 'BELLO', 'What else are you good for, an impotent thing like you? {he stoops and, peering, pokes with his fan rudely under the fat suet folds of Bloom''s haunches} Up! Up! Manx cat! What have we here? Where''s your curly teapot gone to or who docked it on you, cockyolly? Sing, birdy, sing. It''s as limp as a boy of six''s doing his pooly behind a cart. Buy a bucket or sell your pump. {loudly} Can you do a man''s job? ', 'What else are you good for, an impotent thing like you?   Up! Up! Manx cat! What have we here? Where''s your curly teapot gone to or who docked it on you, cockyolly? Sing, birdy, sing. It''s as limp as a boy of six''s doing his pooly behind a cart. Buy a bucket or sell your pump.   Can you do a man''s job? ', '{he stoops and, peering, pokes with his fan rudely under the fat suet folds of Bloom''s haunches},{loudly}'),
(642, 'BLOOM', 'Eccles street.... ', 'Eccles street.... ', ''),
(643, 'BELLO', '{sarcastically} I wouldn''t hurt your feelings for the world but there''s a man of brawn in possession there. The tables are turned, my gay young fellow! He is something like a fullgrown outdoor man. Well for you, you muff, if you had that weapon with knobs and lumps and warts all over it. He shot his bolt, I can tell you! Foot to foot, knee to knee, belly to belly, bubs to breast! He''s no eunuch. A shock of red hair he has sticking out of him behind like a furzebush! Wait for nine months, my lad! Holy ginger, it''s kicking and coughing up and down in her guts already! That makes you wild, don''t it? Touches the spot? {he spits in contempt} Spittoon! ', '  I wouldn''t hurt your feelings for the world but there''s a man of brawn in possession there. The tables are turned, my gay young fellow! He is something like a fullgrown outdoor man. Well for you, you muff, if you had that weapon with knobs and lumps and warts all over it. He shot his bolt, I can tell you! Foot to foot, knee to knee, belly to belly, bubs to breast! He''s no eunuch. A shock of red hair he has sticking out of him behind like a furzebush! Wait for nine months, my lad! Holy ginger, it''s kicking and coughing up and down in her guts already! That makes you wild, don''t it? Touches the spot?   Spittoon! ', '{sarcastically},{he spits in contempt}'),
(644, 'BLOOM', 'I was indecently treated, I ..... Inform the police. Hundred pounds. Unmentionable. I .... ', 'I was indecently treated, I ..... Inform the police. Hundred pounds. Unmentionable. I .... ', ''),
(645, 'BELLO', 'Would if you could, lame duck. A downpour we want not your drizzle. ', 'Would if you could, lame duck. A downpour we want not your drizzle. ', ''),
(646, 'BLOOM', 'To drive me mad! Moll! I forgot! Forgive! Moll .... We .... Still ..... ', 'To drive me mad! Moll! I forgot! Forgive! Moll .... We .... Still ..... ', ''),
(647, 'BELLO', '{ruthlessly} No, Leopold Bloom, all is changed by woman''s will since you slept horizontal in Sleepy Hollow your night of twenty years. Return and see. {Old Sleepy Hollow calls over the wold.} ', '  No, Leopold Bloom, all is changed by woman''s will since you slept horizontal in Sleepy Hollow your night of twenty years. Return and see.   ', '{ruthlessly},{Old Sleepy Hollow calls over the wold.}'),
(648, 'SLEEPY HOLLOW', 'Rip van Wink! Rip van Winkle! ', 'Rip van Wink! Rip van Winkle! ', ''),
(649, 'BLOOM', '{in tattered mocassins with a rusty fowlingpiece, tiptoeing, fingertipping, his haggard bony bearded face peering through the diamond panes, cries out} I see her! It''s she! The first night at Mat Dillon''s! But that dress, the green! And her hair is dyed gold and he .... ', '  I see her! It''s she! The first night at Mat Dillon''s! But that dress, the green! And her hair is dyed gold and he .... ', '{in tattered mocassins with a rusty fowlingpiece, tiptoeing, fingertipping, his haggard bony bearded face peering through the diamond panes, cries out}'),
(650, 'BELLO', '{laughs mockingly} That''s your daughter, you owl, with a Mullingar student. {Milly Bloom, fairhaired, greenvested, slimsandalled, her blue scarf in the seawind simply swirling, breaks from the arms of her lover and calls, her young eyes wonderwide.} ', '  That''s your daughter, you owl, with a Mullingar student.   ', '{laughs mockingly},{Milly Bloom, fairhaired, greenvested, slimsandalled, her blue scarf in the seawind simply swirling, breaks from the arms of her lover and calls, her young eyes wonderwide.}'),
(651, 'MILLY', 'My! It''s Papli! But, O Papli, how old you''ve grown! ', 'My! It''s Papli! But, O Papli, how old you''ve grown! ', ''),
(652, 'BELLO', 'Changed, eh? Our whatnot, our writingtable where we never wrote, aunt Hegarty''s armchair, our classic reprints of old masters. A man and his menfriends are living there in clover. The Cuckoos'' Rest! Why not? How many women had you, eh, following them up dark streets, flatfoot, exciting them by your smothered grunts, what, you male prostitute? Blameless dames with parcels of groceries. Turn about. Sauce for the goose, my gander O. ', 'Changed, eh? Our whatnot, our writingtable where we never wrote, aunt Hegarty''s armchair, our classic reprints of old masters. A man and his menfriends are living there in clover. The Cuckoos'' Rest! Why not? How many women had you, eh, following them up dark streets, flatfoot, exciting them by your smothered grunts, what, you male prostitute? Blameless dames with parcels of groceries. Turn about. Sauce for the goose, my gander O. ', ''),
(653, 'BLOOM', 'They.... I .... ', 'They.... I .... ', ''),
(654, 'BELLO', '{cuttingly} Their heelmarks will stamp the Brusselette carpet you bought at Wren''s auction. In their horseplay with Moll the romp to find the buck flea in her breeches they will deface the little statue you carried home in the rain for art for art'' sake. They will violate the secrets of your bottom drawer. Pages will be torn from your handbook of astronomy to make them pipespills. And they will spit in your ten shilling brass fender from Hampton Leedom''s. ', '  Their heelmarks will stamp the Brusselette carpet you bought at Wren''s auction. In their horseplay with Moll the romp to find the buck flea in her breeches they will deface the little statue you carried home in the rain for art for art'' sake. They will violate the secrets of your bottom drawer. Pages will be torn from your handbook of astronomy to make them pipespills. And they will spit in your ten shilling brass fender from Hampton Leedom''s. ', '{cuttingly}'),
(655, 'BLOOM', 'Ten and six. The act of low scoundrels. Let me go. I will return. I will prove ... ', 'Ten and six. The act of low scoundrels. Let me go. I will return. I will prove ... ', ''),
(656, 'A VOICE', 'Swear! {Bloom clenches his fists and crawls forward, a bowieknife between his teeth.} ', 'Swear!   ', '{Bloom clenches his fists and crawls forward, a bowieknife between his teeth.}'),
(657, 'BELLO', 'As a paying guest or a kept man? Too late. You have made your secondbest bed and others must lie in it. Your epitaph is written. You are down and out and don''t you forget it, old bean. ', 'As a paying guest or a kept man? Too late. You have made your secondbest bed and others must lie in it. Your epitaph is written. You are down and out and don''t you forget it, old bean. ', ''),
(658, 'BLOOM', 'Justice! All Ireland versus one! Has nobody ...? {he bites his thumb} ', 'Justice! All Ireland versus one! Has nobody ...?   ', '{he bites his thumb}'),
(659, 'BELLO', 'Die and be damned to you if you have any sense of decency or grace about you. I can give you a rare old wine that''ll send you skipping to hell and back. Sign a will and leave us any coin you have! If you have none see you damn well get it, steal it, rob it! We''ll bury you in our shrubbery jakes where you''ll be dead and dirty with old Cuck Cohen, my stepnephew I married, the bloody old gouty procurator and sodomite with a crick in his neck, and my other ten or eleven husbands, whatever the buggers'' names were, suffocated in the one cesspool. {he explodes in a loud phlegmy laugh} We''ll manure you, Mr Flower! {he pipes scoffingly} Byby, Poldy! Byby, Papli! ', 'Die and be damned to you if you have any sense of decency or grace about you. I can give you a rare old wine that''ll send you skipping to hell and back. Sign a will and leave us any coin you have! If you have none see you damn well get it, steal it, rob it! We''ll bury you in our shrubbery jakes where you''ll be dead and dirty with old Cuck Cohen, my stepnephew I married, the bloody old gouty procurator and sodomite with a crick in his neck, and my other ten or eleven husbands, whatever the buggers'' names were, suffocated in the one cesspool.   We''ll manure you, Mr Flower!   Byby, Poldy! Byby, Papli! ', '{he explodes in a loud phlegmy laugh},{he pipes scoffingly}'),
(660, 'BLOOM', '{clasps his head} My willpower! Memory! I have sinned! I have suff.... {he weeps tearlessly} ', '  My willpower! Memory! I have sinned! I have suff....   ', '{clasps his head},{he weeps tearlessly}'),
(661, 'BELLO', '{sneers} Crybabby! Crocodile tears! {Bloom, broken, closely veiled for the sacrifice, sobs, his face to the earth. The passing bell is heard. Darkshawled figures of the circumcised, in sackcloth and ashes, stand by the wailing wall, M. Shulomowitz, Joseph Goldwater, Moses Herzog, Harris Rosenberg, M. Moisel, J. Citron, Minnie Watchman, P. Mastiansky, the reverend Leopold Abramovitz, chazen. With swaying arms they wail in pneuma over the recreant Bloom.} ', '  Crybabby! Crocodile tears!   ', '{sneers},{Bloom, broken, closely veiled for the sacrifice, sobs, his face to the earth. The passing bell is heard. Darkshawled figures of the circumcised, in sackcloth and ashes, stand by the wailing wall, M. Shulomowitz, Joseph Goldwater, Moses Herzog, Harris Rosenberg, M. Moisel, J. Citron, Minnie Watchman, P. Mastiansky, the reverend Leopold Abramovitz, chazen. With swaying arms they wail in pneuma over the recreant Bloom.}'),
(662, 'THE CIRCUMCISED', '{in dark guttural chant as they cast dead sea fruit upon him, no flowers} Shema Israel Adonai Elohenu Adonai Echad. ', '  Shema Israel Adonai Elohenu Adonai Echad. ', '{in dark guttural chant as they cast dead sea fruit upon him, no flowers}'),
(663, 'VOICES', '{sighing} So he''s gone. Ah yes. Yes, indeed. Bloom? Never heard of him. No? Queer kind of chap. There''s the widow. That so? Ah, yes. {From the suttee pyre the flame of gum camphire ascends. The pall of incense smoke screens and disperses. Out of her oakframe a nymph with hair unbound, lightly clad in teabrown artcolours, descends from her grotto and passing under interlacing yews stands over Bloom.} ', '  So he''s gone. Ah yes. Yes, indeed. Bloom? Never heard of him. No? Queer kind of chap. There''s the widow. That so? Ah, yes.   ', '{sighing},{From the suttee pyre the flame of gum camphire ascends. The pall of incense smoke screens and disperses. Out of her oakframe a nymph with hair unbound, lightly clad in teabrown artcolours, descends from her grotto and passing under interlacing yews stands over Bloom.}'),
(664, 'THE YEWS', '{their leaves whispering} Sister. Our sister. Ssh! ', '  Sister. Our sister. Ssh! ', '{their leaves whispering}'),
(665, 'THE NYMPH', '{softly} Mortal! {kindly} Nay, dost not weepest! ', '  Mortal!   Nay, dost not weepest! ', '{softly},{kindly}'),
(666, 'BLOOM', '{crawls jellily forward under the boughs, streaked by sunlight, with dignity} This position. I felt it was expected of me. Force of habit. ', '  This position. I felt it was expected of me. Force of habit. ', '{crawls jellily forward under the boughs, streaked by sunlight, with dignity}'),
(667, 'THE NYMPH', 'Mortal! You found me in evil company, highkickers, coster picnicmakers, pugilists, popular generals, immoral panto boys in fleshtights and the nifty shimmy dancers, La Aurora and Karini, musical act, the hit of the century. I was hidden in cheap pink paper that smelt of rock oil. I was surrounded by the stale smut of clubmen, stories to disturb callow youth, ads for transparencies, truedup dice and bustpads, proprietary articles and why wear a truss with testimonial from ruptured gentleman. Useful hints to the married. ', 'Mortal! You found me in evil company, highkickers, coster picnicmakers, pugilists, popular generals, immoral panto boys in fleshtights and the nifty shimmy dancers, La Aurora and Karini, musical act, the hit of the century. I was hidden in cheap pink paper that smelt of rock oil. I was surrounded by the stale smut of clubmen, stories to disturb callow youth, ads for transparencies, truedup dice and bustpads, proprietary articles and why wear a truss with testimonial from ruptured gentleman. Useful hints to the married. ', ''),
(668, 'BLOOM', '{lifts a turtle head towards her lap} We have met before. On another star. ', '  We have met before. On another star. ', '{lifts a turtle head towards her lap}'),
(669, 'THE NYMPH', '{sadly} Rubber goods. Neverrip brand as supplied to the aristocracy. Corsets for men. I cure fits or money refunded. Unsolicited testimonials for Professor Waldmann''s wonderful chest exuber. My bust developed four inches in three weeks, reports Mrs Gus Rublin with photo. ', '  Rubber goods. Neverrip brand as supplied to the aristocracy. Corsets for men. I cure fits or money refunded. Unsolicited testimonials for Professor Waldmann''s wonderful chest exuber. My bust developed four inches in three weeks, reports Mrs Gus Rublin with photo. ', '{sadly}'),
(670, 'BLOOM', 'You mean Photo Bits? ', 'You mean Photo Bits? ', ''),
(671, 'THE NYMPH', 'I do. You bore me away, framed me in oak and tinsel, set me above your marriage couch. Unseen, one summer eve, you kissed me in four places. And with loving pencil you shaded my eyes, my bosom and my shame. ', 'I do. You bore me away, framed me in oak and tinsel, set me above your marriage couch. Unseen, one summer eve, you kissed me in four places. And with loving pencil you shaded my eyes, my bosom and my shame. ', ''),
(672, 'BLOOM', '{humbly kisses her long hair} Your classic curves, beautiful immortal, I was glad to look on you, to praise you, a thing of beauty, almost to pray. ', '  Your classic curves, beautiful immortal, I was glad to look on you, to praise you, a thing of beauty, almost to pray. ', '{humbly kisses her long hair}'),
(673, 'THE NYMPH', 'During dark nights I heard your praise. ', 'During dark nights I heard your praise. ', ''),
(674, 'BLOOM', '{quickly} Yes, yes. You mean that I.... Sleep reveals the worst side of everyone, children perhaps excepted. I know I fell out of bed or rather was pushed. Steel wine is said to cure snoring. For the rest there is that English invention, pamphlet of which I received some days ago, incorrectly addressed. It claims to afford a noiseless, inoffensive vent. {he sighs} ''Twas ever thus. Frailty, thy name is marriage. ', '  Yes, yes. You mean that I.... Sleep reveals the worst side of everyone, children perhaps excepted. I know I fell out of bed or rather was pushed. Steel wine is said to cure snoring. For the rest there is that English invention, pamphlet of which I received some days ago, incorrectly addressed. It claims to afford a noiseless, inoffensive vent.   ''Twas ever thus. Frailty, thy name is marriage. ', '{quickly},{he sighs}'),
(675, 'THE NYMPH', '{her fingers in her ears} And words. They are not in my dictionary. ', '  And words. They are not in my dictionary. ', '{her fingers in her ears}'),
(676, 'BLOOM', 'You understood them? ', 'You understood them? ', ''),
(677, 'THE YEWS', 'Ssh! ', 'Ssh! ', ''),
(678, 'THE NYMPH', '{covers her face with her hands} What have I not seen in that chamber? What must my eyes look down on? ', '  What have I not seen in that chamber? What must my eyes look down on? ', '{covers her face with her hands}'),
(679, 'BLOOM', '{apologetically} I know. Soiled personal linen, wrong side up with care. The quoits are loose. From Gibraltar by long sea long ago. ', '  I know. Soiled personal linen, wrong side up with care. The quoits are loose. From Gibraltar by long sea long ago. ', '{apologetically}'),
(680, 'THE NYMPH', '{bends her head} Worse, worse! ', '  Worse, worse! ', '{bends her head}'),
(681, 'BLOOM', '{reflects precautiously} That antiquated commode. It wasn''t her weight. She scaled just eleven stone nine. She put on nine pounds after weaning. It was a crack and want of glue. Eh? And that absurd orangekeyed utensil which has only one handle. {The sound of a waterfall is heard in bright cascade.} ', '  That antiquated commode. It wasn''t her weight. She scaled just eleven stone nine. She put on nine pounds after weaning. It was a crack and want of glue. Eh? And that absurd orangekeyed utensil which has only one handle.   ', '{reflects precautiously},{The sound of a waterfall is heard in bright cascade.}'),
(682, 'THE WATERFALL', 'Poulaphouca Poulaphouca Poulaphouca Poulaphouca. ', 'Poulaphouca Poulaphouca Poulaphouca Poulaphouca. ', ''),
(683, 'THE YEWS', '{mingling their boughs} Listen. Whisper. She is right, our sister. We grew by Poulaphouca waterfall. We gave shade on languorous summer days. ', '  Listen. Whisper. She is right, our sister. We grew by Poulaphouca waterfall. We gave shade on languorous summer days. ', '{mingling their boughs}'),
(684, 'JOHN WYSE NOLAN', '{in the background, in Irish National Forester''s uniform, doffs his plumed hat} Prosper! Give shade on languorous days, trees of Ireland! ', '  Prosper! Give shade on languorous days, trees of Ireland! ', '{in the background, in Irish National Forester''s uniform, doffs his plumed hat}'),
(685, 'THE YEWS', '{murmuring} Who came to Poulaphouca with the High School excursion? Who left his nutquesting classmates to seek our shade? ', '  Who came to Poulaphouca with the High School excursion? Who left his nutquesting classmates to seek our shade? ', '{murmuring}'),
(686, 'BLOOM', '{scared} High School of Poula? Mnemo? Not in full possession of faculties. Concussion. Run over by tram. ', '  High School of Poula? Mnemo? Not in full possession of faculties. Concussion. Run over by tram. ', '{scared}'),
(687, 'THE ECHO', 'Sham! ', 'Sham! ', ''),
(688, 'BLOOM', '{pigeonbreasted, bottleshouldered, padded, in nondescript juvenile grey and black striped suit, too small for him, white tennis shoes, bordered stockings with turnover tops and a red schoolcap with badge} I was in my teens, a growing boy. A little then sufficed, a jolting car, the mingling odours of the ladies'' cloakroom and lavatory, the throng penned tight on the old Royal stairs (for they love crushes, instinct of the herd, and the dark sexsmelling theatre unbridles vice), even a pricelist of their hosiery. And then the heat. There were sunspots that summer. End of school. And tipsycake. Halcyon days. {Halcyon Days, High School boys in blue and white football jerseys and shorts, Master Donald Turnbull, Master Abraham Chatterton, Master Owen Goldberg, Master Jack Meredith, Master Percy Apjohn, stand in a clearing of the trees and shout to Master Leopold Bloom.} ', '  I was in my teens, a growing boy. A little then sufficed, a jolting car, the mingling odours of the ladies'' cloakroom and lavatory, the throng penned tight on the old Royal stairs (for they love crushes, instinct of the herd, and the dark sexsmelling theatre unbridles vice), even a pricelist of their hosiery. And then the heat. There were sunspots that summer. End of school. And tipsycake. Halcyon days.   ', '{pigeonbreasted, bottleshouldered, padded, in nondescript juvenile grey and black striped suit, too small for him, white tennis shoes, bordered stockings with turnover tops and a red schoolcap with badge},{Halcyon Days, High School boys in blue and white football jerseys and shorts, Master Donald Turnbull, Master Abraham Chatterton, Master Owen Goldberg, Master Jack Meredith, Master Percy Apjohn, stand in a clearing of the trees and shout to Master Leopold Bloom.}'),
(689, 'THE HALCYON DAYS', 'Mackerel! Live us again. Hurray! {they cheer} ', 'Mackerel! Live us again. Hurray!   ', '{they cheer}'),
(690, 'BLOOM', '{hobbledehoy, warmgloved, mammamufflered, starred with spent snowballs, struggles to rise} Again! I feel sixteen! What a lark! Let''s ring all the bells in Montague street. {he cheers feebly} Hurray for the High School! ', '  Again! I feel sixteen! What a lark! Let''s ring all the bells in Montague street.   Hurray for the High School! ', '{hobbledehoy, warmgloved, mammamufflered, starred with spent snowballs, struggles to rise},{he cheers feebly}'),
(691, 'THE ECHO', 'Fool! ', 'Fool! ', ''),
(692, 'THE YEWS', '{rustling} She is right, our sister. Whisper. {Whispered kisses are heard in all the wood. Faces of hamadryads peep out from the boles and among the leaves and break, blossoming into bloom.} Who profaned our silent shade? ', '  She is right, our sister. Whisper.   Who profaned our silent shade? ', '{rustling},{Whispered kisses are heard in all the wood. Faces of hamadryads peep out from the boles and among the leaves and break, blossoming into bloom.}'),
(693, 'THE NYMPH', '{coyly, through parting fingers} There? In the open air? ', '  There? In the open air? ', '{coyly, through parting fingers}'),
(694, 'THE YEWS', '{sweeping downward} Sister, yes. And on our virgin sward. ', '  Sister, yes. And on our virgin sward. ', '{sweeping downward}'),
(695, 'THE WATERFALL', 'Poulaphouca Poulaphouca Phoucaphouca Phoucaphouca. ', 'Poulaphouca Poulaphouca Phoucaphouca Phoucaphouca. ', ''),
(696, 'THE NYMPH', '{with wide fingers} O, infamy! ', '  O, infamy! ', '{with wide fingers}'),
(697, 'BLOOM', 'I was precocious. Youth. The fauna. I sacrificed to the god of the forest. The flowers that bloom in the spring. It was pairing time. Capillary attraction is a natural phenomenon. Lotty Clarke, flaxenhaired, I saw at her night toilette through illclosed curtains with poor papa''s operaglasses: The wanton ate grass wildly. She rolled downhill at Rialto bridge to tempt me with her flow of animal spirits. She climbed their crooked tree and I. A saint couldn''t resist it. The demon possessed me. Besides, who saw? {Staggering Bob, a whitepolled calf, thrusts a ruminating head with humid nostrils through the foliage.} ', 'I was precocious. Youth. The fauna. I sacrificed to the god of the forest. The flowers that bloom in the spring. It was pairing time. Capillary attraction is a natural phenomenon. Lotty Clarke, flaxenhaired, I saw at her night toilette through illclosed curtains with poor papa''s operaglasses: The wanton ate grass wildly. She rolled downhill at Rialto bridge to tempt me with her flow of animal spirits. She climbed their crooked tree and I. A saint couldn''t resist it. The demon possessed me. Besides, who saw?   ', '{Staggering Bob, a whitepolled calf, thrusts a ruminating head with humid nostrils through the foliage.}'),
(698, 'STAGGERING BOB', '{large teardrops rolling from his prominent eyes, snivels} Me. Me see. ', '  Me. Me see. ', '{large teardrops rolling from his prominent eyes, snivels}'),
(699, 'BLOOM', 'Simply satisfying a need. {with pathos} No girl would when I went girling. Too ugly. They wouldn''t play .... {High on Ben Howth through rhododendrons a nannygoat passes, plumpuddered, buttytailed, dropping currants.} ', 'Simply satisfying a need.   No girl would when I went girling. Too ugly. They wouldn''t play ....   ', '{with pathos},{High on Ben Howth through rhododendrons a nannygoat passes, plumpuddered, buttytailed, dropping currants.}'),
(700, 'THE NANNYGOAT', '{bleats} Megeggaggegg! Nannannanny! ', '  Megeggaggegg! Nannannanny! ', '{bleats}'),
(701, 'BLOOM', '{hatless, flushed, covered with burrs of thistledown and gorsespine} Regularly engaged. Circumstances alter cases. {he gazes intently downwards on the water} Thirtytwo head over heels per second. Press nightmare. Giddy Elijah. Fall from cliff. Sad end of government printer''s clerk. {Through silversilent summer air the dummy of Bloom, rolled in a mummy, rolls roteatingly from the Lion''s Head cliff into the purple waiting waters.} ', '  Regularly engaged. Circumstances alter cases.   Thirtytwo head over heels per second. Press nightmare. Giddy Elijah. Fall from cliff. Sad end of government printer''s clerk.   ', '{hatless, flushed, covered with burrs of thistledown and gorsespine},{he gazes intently downwards on the water},{Through silversilent summer air the dummy of Bloom, rolled in a mummy, rolls roteatingly from the Lion''s Head cliff into the purple waiting waters.}'),
(702, 'THE DUMMYMUMMY', 'Bbbbblllllblblblblobschb! {Far out in the bay between Bailey and Kish lights the Erin''s King sails, sending a broadening plume of coalsmoke from her funnel towards the land.} ', 'Bbbbblllllblblblblobschb!   ', '{Far out in the bay between Bailey and Kish lights the Erin''s King sails, sending a broadening plume of coalsmoke from her funnel towards the land.}'),
(703, 'COUNCILLOR NANNETII', '{lone on deck, in dark alpaca, yellowkitefaced, his hand in his waistcoat opening, declaims} When my country takes her place among the nations of the earth, then, and not till then, let my epitaph be written. I have ... ', '  When my country takes her place among the nations of the earth, then, and not till then, let my epitaph be written. I have ... ', '{lone on deck, in dark alpaca, yellowkitefaced, his hand in his waistcoat opening, declaims}'),
(704, 'BLOOM', 'Done. Prff! ', 'Done. Prff! ', ''),
(705, 'THE NYMPH', '{loftily} We immortals, as you saw today, have not such a place and no hair there either. We are stonecold and pure. We eat electric light. {she arches her body in lascivious crispation, placing her forefinger in her mouth} Spoke to me. Heard from behind. How then could you ...? ', '  We immortals, as you saw today, have not such a place and no hair there either. We are stonecold and pure. We eat electric light.   Spoke to me. Heard from behind. How then could you ...? ', '{loftily},{she arches her body in lascivious crispation, placing her forefinger in her mouth}'),
(706, 'BLOOM', '{pawing the heather abjectly} O, I have been a perfect pig. Enemas too I have administered. One third of a pint of quassia to which add a tablespoonful of rocksalt. Up the fundament. With Hamilton Long''s syringe, the ladies'' friend. ', '  O, I have been a perfect pig. Enemas too I have administered. One third of a pint of quassia to which add a tablespoonful of rocksalt. Up the fundament. With Hamilton Long''s syringe, the ladies'' friend. ', '{pawing the heather abjectly}'),
(707, 'THE NYMPH', 'In my presence. The powderpuff. (she blushes and makes a knee} And the rest! ', 'In my presence. The powderpuff. (she blushes and makes a knee} And the rest! ', ''),
(708, 'BLOOM', '{dejected} Yes. Peccavi! I have paid homage on that living altar where the back changes name. {with sudden fervour} For why should the dainty scented jewelled hand, the hand that rules ...? {Figures wind serpenting in slow woodland pattern around the treestems, cooeeing.} ', '  Yes. Peccavi! I have paid homage on that living altar where the back changes name.   For why should the dainty scented jewelled hand, the hand that rules ...?   ', '{dejected},{with sudden fervour},{Figures wind serpenting in slow woodland pattern around the treestems, cooeeing.}'),
(709, 'THE VOICE OF KITTY', '{in the thicket} Show us one of them cushions. ', '  Show us one of them cushions. ', '{in the thicket}'),
(710, 'THE VOICE OF FLORRY', 'Here. {A grouse wings clumsily through the underwood.} ', 'Here.   ', '{A grouse wings clumsily through the underwood.}'),
(711, 'THE VOICE OF LYNCH', '{in the thicket} Whew! Piping hot! ', '  Whew! Piping hot! ', '{in the thicket}'),
(712, 'THE VOICE OF ZOE', '{in the thicket} Came from a hot place. ', '  Came from a hot place. ', '{in the thicket}'),
(713, 'THE VOICE OF VIRAG', '{a birdchief, bluestreaked and feathered in war panoply with his assegai, striding through a crackling canebrake over beechmast and acorns} Hot! Hot! Ware Sitting Bull! ', '  Hot! Hot! Ware Sitting Bull! ', '{a birdchief, bluestreaked and feathered in war panoply with his assegai, striding through a crackling canebrake over beechmast and acorns}'),
(714, 'BLOOM', 'It overpowers me. The warm impress of her warm form. Even to sit where a woman has sat, especially with divaricated thighs, as though to grant the last favours, most especially with previously well uplifted white sateen coatpans. So womanly, full. It fills me full. ', 'It overpowers me. The warm impress of her warm form. Even to sit where a woman has sat, especially with divaricated thighs, as though to grant the last favours, most especially with previously well uplifted white sateen coatpans. So womanly, full. It fills me full. ', ''),
(715, 'THE WATERFALL', 'Phillaphulla Poulaphouca Poulaphouca Poulaphouca. ', 'Phillaphulla Poulaphouca Poulaphouca Poulaphouca. ', ''),
(716, 'THE YEWS', 'Ssh! Sister, speak! ', 'Ssh! Sister, speak! ', ''),
(717, 'THE NYMPH', '{eyeless, in nun''s white habit, coif and hugewinged wimple, softly, with remote eyes} Tranquilla convent. Sister Agatha. Mount Carmel. The apparitions of Knock and Lourdes. No more desire. {she reclines her head, sighing} Only the ethereal. Where dreamy creamy gull waves o''er the waters dull. {Bloom half rises. His back trouserbutton snaps.} ', '  Tranquilla convent. Sister Agatha. Mount Carmel. The apparitions of Knock and Lourdes. No more desire.   Only the ethereal. Where dreamy creamy gull waves o''er the waters dull.   ', '{eyeless, in nun''s white habit, coif and hugewinged wimple, softly, with remote eyes},{she reclines her head, sighing},{Bloom half rises. His back trouserbutton snaps.}'),
(718, 'THE BUTTON', 'Bip! {Two sluts of the Coombe dance rainily by, shawled, yelling flatly.} ', 'Bip!   ', '{Two sluts of the Coombe dance rainily by, shawled, yelling flatly.}'),
(719, 'THE SLUTS', 'O, Leopold lost the pin of his drawers He didn''t know what to do, To keep it up, To keep it up. ', 'O, Leopold lost the pin of his drawers He didn''t know what to do, To keep it up, To keep it up. ', ''),
(720, 'BLOOM', '{coldly} You have broken the spell. The last straw. If there were only ethereal where would you all be, postulants and novices? Shy but willing like an ass pissing. ', '  You have broken the spell. The last straw. If there were only ethereal where would you all be, postulants and novices? Shy but willing like an ass pissing. ', '{coldly}'),
(721, 'THE YEWS', '{their silverfoil of leaves precipitating, their skinny arms aging and swaying} Deciduously! ', '  Deciduously! ', '{their silverfoil of leaves precipitating, their skinny arms aging and swaying}'),
(722, 'THE NYMPH', '{her features hardening, gropes in the folds of her habit} Sacrilege! To attempt my virtue! {a large moist stain appears on her robe} Sully my innocence! You are not fit to touch the garment of a pure woman. {she clutches again in her robe} Wait. Satan, you''ll sing no more lovesongs. Amen. Amen. Amen. Amen. {she draws a poniard and, clad in the sheathmail of an elected knight of nine, strikes at his loins} Nekum! ', '  Sacrilege! To attempt my virtue!   Sully my innocence! You are not fit to touch the garment of a pure woman.   Wait. Satan, you''ll sing no more lovesongs. Amen. Amen. Amen. Amen.   Nekum! ', '{her features hardening, gropes in the folds of her habit},{a large moist stain appears on her robe},{she clutches again in her robe},{she draws a poniard and, clad in the sheathmail of an elected knight of nine, strikes at his loins}'),
(723, 'BLOOM', '{starts up, seizes her hand} Hoy! Nebrakada! Cat o'' nine lives! Fair play, madam. No pruningknife. The fox and the grapes, is it? What do you lack with your barbed wire? Crucifix not thick enough? {he clutches her veil} A holy abbot you want or Brophy, the lame gardener, or the spoutless statue of the watercarrier, or good mother Alphonsus, eh Reynard? ', '  Hoy! Nebrakada! Cat o'' nine lives! Fair play, madam. No pruningknife. The fox and the grapes, is it? What do you lack with your barbed wire? Crucifix not thick enough?   A holy abbot you want or Brophy, the lame gardener, or the spoutless statue of the watercarrier, or good mother Alphonsus, eh Reynard? ', '{starts up, seizes her hand},{he clutches her veil}'),
(724, 'THE NYMPH', '{with a cry flees from him unveiled, her plaster cast cracking, a cloud of stench escaping from the cracks} Poli ...! ', '  Poli ...! ', '{with a cry flees from him unveiled, her plaster cast cracking, a cloud of stench escaping from the cracks}'),
(725, 'BLOOM', '{calls after her} As if you didn''t get it on the double yourselves. No jerks and multiple mucosities all over you. I tried it. Your strength our weakness. What''s our studfee? What will you pay on the nail? You fee mendancers on the Riviera, I read. {the fleeing nymph raises a keen} Eh? I have sixteen years of black slave labour behind me. And would a jury give me five shillings alimony tomorrow, eh? Fool someone else, not me. {he sniffs} Rut. Onions. Stale. Sulphur. Grease. {The figure of Bella Cohen stands before him.} ', '  As if you didn''t get it on the double yourselves. No jerks and multiple mucosities all over you. I tried it. Your strength our weakness. What''s our studfee? What will you pay on the nail? You fee mendancers on the Riviera, I read.   Eh? I have sixteen years of black slave labour behind me. And would a jury give me five shillings alimony tomorrow, eh? Fool someone else, not me.   Rut. Onions. Stale. Sulphur. Grease.   ', '{calls after her},{the fleeing nymph raises a keen},{he sniffs},{The figure of Bella Cohen stands before him.}'),
(726, 'BELLA', 'You''ll know me the next time. ', 'You''ll know me the next time. ', ''),
(727, 'BLOOM', '{composed, regards her} Passée. Mutton dressed as lamb. Long in the tooth and superfluous hair. A raw onion the last thing at night would benefit your complexion. And take some double chin drill. Your eyes are as vapid as the glasseyes of your stuffed fox. They have the dimensions of your other features, that''s all. I''m not a triple screw propeller. ', '  Passée. Mutton dressed as lamb. Long in the tooth and superfluous hair. A raw onion the last thing at night would benefit your complexion. And take some double chin drill. Your eyes are as vapid as the glasseyes of your stuffed fox. They have the dimensions of your other features, that''s all. I''m not a triple screw propeller. ', '{composed, regards her}'),
(728, 'BELLA', '{contemptuously} You''re not game, in fact. {her sowcunt barks} Fbhracht! ', '  You''re not game, in fact.   Fbhracht! ', '{contemptuously},{her sowcunt barks}'),
(729, 'BLOOM', '{contemptuously} Clean your nailless middle finger first, your bully''s cold spunk is dripping from your cockscomb. Take a handful of hay and wipe yourself. ', '  Clean your nailless middle finger first, your bully''s cold spunk is dripping from your cockscomb. Take a handful of hay and wipe yourself. ', '{contemptuously}'),
(730, 'BELLA', 'I know you, canvasser! Dead cod! ', 'I know you, canvasser! Dead cod! ', ''),
(731, 'BLOOM', 'I saw him, kipkeeper! Pox and gleet vendor! ', 'I saw him, kipkeeper! Pox and gleet vendor! ', ''),
(732, 'BELLA', '{turns to the piano} Which of you was playing the dead march from Saul? ', '  Which of you was playing the dead march from Saul? ', '{turns to the piano}'),
(733, 'ZOE', 'Me. Mind your cornflowers. {she darts to the piano and bangs chords on it with crossed arms} The cat''s ramble through the slag. {she glances back} Eh? Who''s making love to my sweeties? {she darts back to the table} What''s yours is mine and what''s mine is my own. {Kitty, disconcerted, coats her teeth with the silver paper. Bloom approaches Zoe.} ', 'Me. Mind your cornflowers.   The cat''s ramble through the slag.   Eh? Who''s making love to my sweeties?   What''s yours is mine and what''s mine is my own.   ', '{she darts to the piano and bangs chords on it with crossed arms},{she glances back},{she darts back to the table},{Kitty, disconcerted, coats her teeth with the silver paper. Bloom approaches Zoe.}'),
(734, 'BLOOM', '{gently} Give me back that potato, will you? ', '  Give me back that potato, will you? ', '{gently}'),
(735, 'ZOE', 'Forfeits, a fine thing and a superfine thing. ', 'Forfeits, a fine thing and a superfine thing. ', ''),
(736, 'BLOOM', '{with feeling} It is nothing, but still, a relic of poor mamma. ', '  It is nothing, but still, a relic of poor mamma. ', '{with feeling}'),
(737, 'ZOE', 'Give a thing and take it back God''ll ask you where is that You''ll say you don''t know God''ll send you down below. ', 'Give a thing and take it back God''ll ask you where is that You''ll say you don''t know God''ll send you down below. ', ''),
(738, 'BLOOM', 'There is a memory attached to it. I should like to have it. ', 'There is a memory attached to it. I should like to have it. ', ''),
(739, 'STEPHEN', 'To have or not to have that is the question. ', 'To have or not to have that is the question. ', ''),
(740, 'ZOE', 'Here. {she hauls up a reef of her slip, revealing her bare thigh, and unrolls the potato from the top of her stocking} Those that hides knows where to find. ', 'Here.   Those that hides knows where to find. ', '{she hauls up a reef of her slip, revealing her bare thigh, and unrolls the potato from the top of her stocking}'),
(741, 'BELLA', '{frowns} Here. This isn''t a musical peepshow. And don''t you smash that piano. Who''s paying here? {She goes to the pianola. Stephen fumbles in his pocket and, taking out a banknote by its corner, hands it to her.} ', '  Here. This isn''t a musical peepshow. And don''t you smash that piano. Who''s paying here?   ', '{frowns},{She goes to the pianola. Stephen fumbles in his pocket and, taking out a banknote by its corner, hands it to her.}'),
(742, 'STEPHEN', '{with exaggerated politeness} This silken purse I made out of the sow''s ear of the public. Madam, excuse me. If you allow me. {he indicates vaguely Lynch and Bloom} We are all in the same sweepstake, Kinch and Lynch. Dans ce bordel où tenons nostre état. ', '  This silken purse I made out of the sow''s ear of the public. Madam, excuse me. If you allow me.   We are all in the same sweepstake, Kinch and Lynch. Dans ce bordel où tenons nostre état. ', '{with exaggerated politeness},{he indicates vaguely Lynch and Bloom}'),
(743, 'LYNCH', '{calls from the hearth} Dedalus! Give her your blessing for me. ', '  Dedalus! Give her your blessing for me. ', '{calls from the hearth}'),
(744, 'STEPHEN', '{hands Bella a coin} Gold. She has it. ', '  Gold. She has it. ', '{hands Bella a coin}');
INSERT INTO `circe` (`id`, `speaker`, `full`, `spoken`, `directions`) VALUES
(745, 'BELLA', '{looks at the money, then at Stephen, then at Zoe, Florry and Kitty} Do you want three girls? It''s ten shillings here. ', '  Do you want three girls? It''s ten shillings here. ', '{looks at the money, then at Stephen, then at Zoe, Florry and Kitty}'),
(746, 'STEPHEN', '{delightedly} A hundred thousand apologies. {he fumbles again and takes out and hands her two crowns} Permit, brevi manu, my sight is somewhat troubled. {Bella goes to the table to count the money while Stephen talks to himself in monosyllables. Zoe bends over the table. Kitty leans over Zoe''s neck. Lynch gets up, rights his cap and, clasping Kitty''s waist, adds his head to the group.} ', '  A hundred thousand apologies.   Permit, brevi manu, my sight is somewhat troubled.   ', '{delightedly},{he fumbles again and takes out and hands her two crowns},{Bella goes to the table to count the money while Stephen talks to himself in monosyllables. Zoe bends over the table. Kitty leans over Zoe''s neck. Lynch gets up, rights his cap and, clasping Kitty''s waist, adds his head to the group.}'),
(747, 'FLORRY', '{strives heavily to rise} Ow! My foot''s asleep. {She limps over to the table. Bloom approaches.} ', '  Ow! My foot''s asleep.   ', '{strives heavily to rise},{She limps over to the table. Bloom approaches.}'),
(748, 'BELLA, ZOE, KITTY, LYNCH, BLOOM', '{chattering and squabbling} The gentleman... ten shillings.... paying for the three... allow me a moment... this gentleman pays separate.... who''s touching it?... ow!... mind who you''re pinching... are you staying the night or a short time?... who did?... you''re a liar, excuse me... the gentleman paid down like a gentleman ... drink ... it''s long after eleven. ', '  The gentleman... ten shillings.... paying for the three... allow me a moment... this gentleman pays separate.... who''s touching it?... ow!... mind who you''re pinching... are you staying the night or a short time?... who did?... you''re a liar, excuse me... the gentleman paid down like a gentleman ... drink ... it''s long after eleven. ', '{chattering and squabbling}'),
(749, 'STEPHEN', '{at the pianola, making a gesture of abhorrence} No bottles! What, eleven? A riddle! ', '  No bottles! What, eleven? A riddle! ', '{at the pianola, making a gesture of abhorrence}'),
(750, 'ZOE', '{lifting up her pettigown and folding a half sovereign into the top of her stocking} Hard earned on the flat of my back. ', '  Hard earned on the flat of my back. ', '{lifting up her pettigown and folding a half sovereign into the top of her stocking}'),
(751, 'LYNCH', '{lifting Kitty from the table} Come! ', '  Come! ', '{lifting Kitty from the table}'),
(752, 'KITTY', 'Wait. {she clutches the two crowns} ', 'Wait.   ', '{she clutches the two crowns}'),
(753, 'FLORRY', 'And me? ', 'And me? ', ''),
(754, 'LYNCH', 'Hoopla! {He lifts her, carries her and bumps her down on the sofa.} ', 'Hoopla!   ', '{He lifts her, carries her and bumps her down on the sofa.}'),
(755, 'STEPHEN', 'The fox crew, the cocks flew, The bells in heaven Were striking eleven. ''Tis time for her poor soul To get out of heaven. ', 'The fox crew, the cocks flew, The bells in heaven Were striking eleven. ''Tis time for her poor soul To get out of heaven. ', ''),
(756, 'BLOOM', '{quietly lays a half sovereign on the table between Bella and Florry} So. Allow me. {he takes up the poundnote} Three times ten. We''re square. ', '  So. Allow me.   Three times ten. We''re square. ', '{quietly lays a half sovereign on the table between Bella and Florry},{he takes up the poundnote}'),
(757, 'BELLA', '{admiringly} You''re such a slyboots, old cocky. I could kiss you. ', '  You''re such a slyboots, old cocky. I could kiss you. ', '{admiringly}'),
(758, 'ZOE', '{points} Him? Deep as a drawwell. {Lynch bends Kitty back over the sofa and kisses her. Bloom goes with the poundnote to Stephen.} ', '  Him? Deep as a drawwell.   ', '{points},{Lynch bends Kitty back over the sofa and kisses her. Bloom goes with the poundnote to Stephen.}'),
(759, 'BLOOM', 'This is yours. ', 'This is yours. ', ''),
(760, 'STEPHEN', 'How is that? The distrait or absentminded beggar. {He fumbles again in his pocket and draws out a handful of coins. An object falls.} That fell. ', 'How is that? The distrait or absentminded beggar.   That fell. ', '{He fumbles again in his pocket and draws out a handful of coins. An object falls.}'),
(761, 'BLOOM', '{stooping, picks up and hands a box of matches} This. ', '  This. ', '{stooping, picks up and hands a box of matches}'),
(762, 'STEPHEN', 'Lucifer. Thanks. ', 'Lucifer. Thanks. ', ''),
(763, 'BLOOM', '{quietly} You had better hand over that cash to me to take care of. Why pay more? ', '  You had better hand over that cash to me to take care of. Why pay more? ', '{quietly}'),
(764, 'STEPHEN', '{hands him all his coins} Be just before you are generous. ', '  Be just before you are generous. ', '{hands him all his coins}'),
(765, 'BLOOM', 'I will but is it wise? {he counts} One, seven, eleven, and five. Six. Eleven. I don''t answer for what you may have lost. ', 'I will but is it wise?   One, seven, eleven, and five. Six. Eleven. I don''t answer for what you may have lost. ', '{he counts}'),
(766, 'STEPHEN', 'Why striking eleven? Proparoxyton. Moment before the next Lessing says. Thirsty fox. {he laughs loudly} Burying his grandmother. Probably he killed her. ', 'Why striking eleven? Proparoxyton. Moment before the next Lessing says. Thirsty fox.   Burying his grandmother. Probably he killed her. ', '{he laughs loudly}'),
(767, 'BLOOM', 'That is one pound six and eleven. One pound seven, say. ', 'That is one pound six and eleven. One pound seven, say. ', ''),
(768, 'STEPHEN', 'Doesn''t matter a rambling damn. ', 'Doesn''t matter a rambling damn. ', ''),
(769, 'BLOOM', 'No, but.... ', 'No, but.... ', ''),
(770, 'STEPHEN', '{comes to the table} Cigarette, please. {Lynch tosses a cigarette from the sofa to the table} And so Georgina Johnson is dead and married. {A cigarette appears on the table. Stephen looks at it.} Wonder. Parlour magic. Married. Hm. {he strikes a match and proceeds to light the cigarette with enigmatic melancholy} ', '  Cigarette, please.   And so Georgina Johnson is dead and married.   Wonder. Parlour magic. Married. Hm.   ', '{comes to the table},{Lynch tosses a cigarette from the sofa to the table},{A cigarette appears on the table. Stephen looks at it.},{he strikes a match and proceeds to light the cigarette with enigmatic melancholy}'),
(771, 'LYNCH', '{watching him} You would have a better chance of lighting it if you held the match nearer. ', '  You would have a better chance of lighting it if you held the match nearer. ', '{watching him}'),
(772, 'STEPHEN', '{brings the match near his eye} Lynx eye. Must get glasses. Broke them yesterday. Sixteen years ago. Distance. The eye sees all flat. {He draws the match away. It goes out.} Brain thinks. Near: far. Ineluctable modality of the visible. {he frowns mysteriously} Hm. Sphinx. The beast that has two backs at midnight. Married. ', '  Lynx eye. Must get glasses. Broke them yesterday. Sixteen years ago. Distance. The eye sees all flat.   Brain thinks. Near: far. Ineluctable modality of the visible.   Hm. Sphinx. The beast that has two backs at midnight. Married. ', '{brings the match near his eye},{He draws the match away. It goes out.},{he frowns mysteriously}'),
(773, 'ZOE', 'It was a commercial traveller married her and took her away with him. ', 'It was a commercial traveller married her and took her away with him. ', ''),
(774, 'FLORRY', '{nods} Mr Lambe from London. ', '  Mr Lambe from London. ', '{nods}'),
(775, 'STEPHEN', 'Lamb of London, who takest away the sins of our world. ', 'Lamb of London, who takest away the sins of our world. ', ''),
(776, 'LYNCH', '{embracing Kitty on the sofa, chants deeply} Dona nobis pacem. {The cigarette slips from Stephen''s fingers. Bloom picks it up and throws it in the grate.} ', '  Dona nobis pacem.   ', '{embracing Kitty on the sofa, chants deeply},{The cigarette slips from Stephen''s fingers. Bloom picks it up and throws it in the grate.}'),
(777, 'BLOOM', 'Don''t smoke. You ought to eat. Cursed dog I met. {to Zoe} You have nothing? ', 'Don''t smoke. You ought to eat. Cursed dog I met.   You have nothing? ', '{to Zoe}'),
(778, 'ZOE', 'Is he hungry? ', 'Is he hungry? ', ''),
(779, 'STEPHEN', '{extends his hand to her smiling and chants to the air of the bloodoath in The Dusk of the Gods} Hangende Hunger, Fragende Frau, Macht uns alle kaputt. ', '  Hangende Hunger, Fragende Frau, Macht uns alle kaputt. ', '{extends his hand to her smiling and chants to the air of the bloodoath in The Dusk of the Gods}'),
(780, 'ZOE', '{tragically} Hamlet, I am thy father''s gimlet! {she takes his hand} Blue eyes beauty I''ll read your hand. {she points to his forehead} No wit, no wrinkles. {she counts} Two, three, Mars, that''s courage. {Stephen shakes his head} No kid. ', '  Hamlet, I am thy father''s gimlet!   Blue eyes beauty I''ll read your hand.   No wit, no wrinkles.   Two, three, Mars, that''s courage.   No kid. ', '{tragically},{she takes his hand},{she points to his forehead},{she counts},{Stephen shakes his head}'),
(781, 'LYNCH', 'Sheet lightning courage. The youth who could not shiver and shake. {to Zoe} Who taught you palmistry? ', 'Sheet lightning courage. The youth who could not shiver and shake.   Who taught you palmistry? ', '{to Zoe}'),
(782, 'ZOE', '{turns} Ask my ballocks that I haven''t got. {to Stephen} I see it in your face. The eye, like that. {she frowns with lowered head} ', '  Ask my ballocks that I haven''t got.   I see it in your face. The eye, like that.   ', '{turns},{to Stephen},{she frowns with lowered head}'),
(783, 'LYNCH', '{laughing, slaps Kitty behind twice} Like that. Pandybat. {Twice loudly a pandybat cracks, the coffin of the pianola flies open, the bald little round jack-in-the-box head of Father Dolan springs up.} ', '  Like that. Pandybat.   ', '{laughing, slaps Kitty behind twice},{Twice loudly a pandybat cracks, the coffin of the pianola flies open, the bald little round jack-in-the-box head of Father Dolan springs up.}'),
(784, 'FATHER DOLAN', 'Any boy want flogging? Broke his glasses? Lazy idle little schemer. See it in your eye. {Mild, benign, rectorial, reproving, the head of Don John Conmee rises from the pianola coffin.} ', 'Any boy want flogging? Broke his glasses? Lazy idle little schemer. See it in your eye.   ', '{Mild, benign, rectorial, reproving, the head of Don John Conmee rises from the pianola coffin.}'),
(785, 'DON JOHN CONMEE', 'Now, Father Dolan! Now. I''m sure that Stephen is a very good little boy! ', 'Now, Father Dolan! Now. I''m sure that Stephen is a very good little boy! ', ''),
(786, 'ZOE', '{examining Stephen''s palm} Woman''s hand. ', '  Woman''s hand. ', '{examining Stephen''s palm}'),
(787, 'STEPHEN', '{murmurs} Continue. Lie. Hold me. Caress. I never could read His handwriting except His criminal thumbprint on the haddock. ', '  Continue. Lie. Hold me. Caress. I never could read His handwriting except His criminal thumbprint on the haddock. ', '{murmurs}'),
(788, 'ZOE', 'What day were you born? ', 'What day were you born? ', ''),
(789, 'STEPHEN', 'Thursday. Today. ', 'Thursday. Today. ', ''),
(790, 'ZOE', 'Thursday''s child has far to go. {she traces lines on his hand} Line of fate. Influential friends. ', 'Thursday''s child has far to go.   Line of fate. Influential friends. ', '{she traces lines on his hand}'),
(791, 'FLORRY', '{pointing} Imagination. ', '  Imagination. ', '{pointing}'),
(792, 'ZOE', 'Mount of the moon. You''ll meet with a .... {she peers at his hands abruptly} I won''t tell you what''s not good for you. Or do you want to know? ', 'Mount of the moon. You''ll meet with a ....   I won''t tell you what''s not good for you. Or do you want to know? ', '{she peers at his hands abruptly}'),
(793, 'BLOOM', '{detaches her fingers and offers his palm} More harm than good. Here. Read mine. ', '  More harm than good. Here. Read mine. ', '{detaches her fingers and offers his palm}'),
(794, 'BELLA', 'Show. {she turns up Bloom''s hand} I thought so. Knobby knuckles for the women. ZOE {peering at Bloom''s palm} Gridiron. Travels beyond the sea and marry money. ', 'Show.   I thought so. Knobby knuckles for the women. ZOE   Gridiron. Travels beyond the sea and marry money. ', '{she turns up Bloom''s hand},{peering at Bloom''s palm}'),
(795, 'BLOOM', 'Wrong. ', 'Wrong. ', ''),
(796, 'ZOE', '{quickly} O, I see. Short little finger. Henpecked husband. That wrong? {Black Liz, a huge rooster hatching in a chalked circle, rises, stretches her wings and clucks.} ', '  O, I see. Short little finger. Henpecked husband. That wrong?   ', '{quickly},{Black Liz, a huge rooster hatching in a chalked circle, rises, stretches her wings and clucks.}'),
(797, 'BLACK LIZ', 'Gara. Klook. Klook. Klook. {she sidles from her newlaid egg and waddles off.} ', 'Gara. Klook. Klook. Klook.   ', '{she sidles from her newlaid egg and waddles off.}'),
(798, 'BLOOM', '{points to his hand} That weal there is an accident. Fell and cut it twentytwo years ago. I was sixteen. ', '  That weal there is an accident. Fell and cut it twentytwo years ago. I was sixteen. ', '{points to his hand}'),
(799, 'ZOE', 'I see, says the blind man. Tell us news. ', 'I see, says the blind man. Tell us news. ', ''),
(800, 'STEPHEN', 'See? Moves to one great goal. I am twentytwo. Sixteen years ago he was twentytwo too. Sixteen years ago I twentytwo tumbled. Twentytwo years ago he sixteen fell off his hobbyhorse. {he winces} Hurt my hand somewhere. Must see a dentist. Money? {Zoe whispers to Florry. They giggle. Bloom releases his hand and writes idly on the table in backhand, pencilling slow curves.} ', 'See? Moves to one great goal. I am twentytwo. Sixteen years ago he was twentytwo too. Sixteen years ago I twentytwo tumbled. Twentytwo years ago he sixteen fell off his hobbyhorse.   Hurt my hand somewhere. Must see a dentist. Money?   ', '{he winces},{Zoe whispers to Florry. They giggle. Bloom releases his hand and writes idly on the table in backhand, pencilling slow curves.}'),
(801, 'FLORRY', 'What? {A hackneycar, number three hundred and twentyfour, with a gallantbuttocked mare, driven by James Barton, Harmony avenue, Donnybrook, trots past. Blazes Boylan and Lenehan sprawl swaying on the sideseats. The Ormond boots crouches behind on the axle. Sadly over the crossblind Lydia Douce and Mina Kennedy gaze.} ', 'What?   ', '{A hackneycar, number three hundred and twentyfour, with a gallantbuttocked mare, driven by James Barton, Harmony avenue, Donnybrook, trots past. Blazes Boylan and Lenehan sprawl swaying on the sideseats. The Ormond boots crouches behind on the axle. Sadly over the crossblind Lydia Douce and Mina Kennedy gaze.}'),
(802, 'THE BOOTS', '{jogging, mocks them with thumb and wriggling wormfingers} Haw haw have you the horn? {Bronze by gold they whisper.} ', '  Haw haw have you the horn?   ', '{jogging, mocks them with thumb and wriggling wormfingers},{Bronze by gold they whisper.}'),
(803, 'ZOE', '{to Florry} Whisper. {she whispers again} {Over the well of the car Blazes Boylan leans, his boater straw set sideways, a red flower in his mouth. Lenehan in yachtsman''s cap and white shoes officiously detaches a long hair from Blazes Boylan''s coat shoulder.} ', '  Whisper.     ', '{to Florry},{she whispers again},{Over the well of the car Blazes Boylan leans, his boater straw set sideways, a red flower in his mouth. Lenehan in yachtsman''s cap and white shoes officiously detaches a long hair from Blazes Boylan''s coat shoulder.}'),
(804, 'LENEHAN', 'Ho! What do I here behold? Were you brushing the cobwebs off a few quims? ', 'Ho! What do I here behold? Were you brushing the cobwebs off a few quims? ', ''),
(805, 'BOYLAN', '{sated, smiles} Plucking a turkey. ', '  Plucking a turkey. ', '{sated, smiles}'),
