(807, 'BOYLAN', '{holding up four thick bluntungulated fingers, winks} Blazes Kate! Up to sample or your money back. {he holds out a forefinger} Smell that. ', '  Blazes Kate! Up to sample or your money back.   Smell that. ', '{holding up four thick bluntungulated fingers, winks},{he holds out a forefinger}'),
(808, 'LENEHAN', '{smells gleefully} Ah! Lobster and mayonnaise. Ah! ', '  Ah! Lobster and mayonnaise. Ah! ', '{smells gleefully}'),
(809, 'ZOE AND FLORRY', '{laugh together} Ha ha ha ha. ', '  Ha ha ha ha. ', '{laugh together}'),
(810, 'BOYLAN', '{jumps surely from the car and calls loudly for all to hear} Hello, Bloom! Mrs Bloom dressed yet? ', '  Hello, Bloom! Mrs Bloom dressed yet? ', '{jumps surely from the car and calls loudly for all to hear}'),
(811, 'BLOOM', '{in flunkey''s prune plush coat and kneebreeches, buff stockings and powdered wig} I''m afraid not, sir. The last articles ..... ', '  I''m afraid not, sir. The last articles ..... ', '{in flunkey''s prune plush coat and kneebreeches, buff stockings and powdered wig}'),
(812, 'BOYLAN', '{tosses him sixpence} Here, to buy yourself a gin and splash. {he hangs his hat smartly on a peg of Bloom''s antlered head} Show me in. I have a little private business with your wife, you understand? ', '  Here, to buy yourself a gin and splash.   Show me in. I have a little private business with your wife, you understand? ', '{tosses him sixpence},{he hangs his hat smartly on a peg of Bloom''s antlered head}'),
(813, 'BLOOM', 'Thank you, sir. Yes, sir. Madam Tweedy is in her bath, sir. ', 'Thank you, sir. Yes, sir. Madam Tweedy is in her bath, sir. ', ''),
(814, 'MARION', 'He ought to feel himself highly honoured. {she plops splashing out of the water} Raoul darling, come and dry me. I''m in my pelt. Only my new hat and a carriage sponge. ', 'He ought to feel himself highly honoured.   Raoul darling, come and dry me. I''m in my pelt. Only my new hat and a carriage sponge. ', '{she plops splashing out of the water}'),
(815, 'BOYLAN', '{a merry twinkle in his eye} Topping! ', '  Topping! ', '{a merry twinkle in his eye}'),
(816, 'BELLA', 'What? What is it? {Zoe whispers to her.} ', 'What? What is it?   ', '{Zoe whispers to her.}'),
(817, 'MARION', 'Let him look, the pishogue! Pimp! And scourge himself! I''ll write to a powerful prostitute or Bartholomona, the bearded woman, to raise weals out on him an inch thick and make him bring me back a signed and stamped receipt. ', 'Let him look, the pishogue! Pimp! And scourge himself! I''ll write to a powerful prostitute or Bartholomona, the bearded woman, to raise weals out on him an inch thick and make him bring me back a signed and stamped receipt. ', ''),
(818, 'BOYLAN', '{clasps himself} Here, I can''t hold this little lot much longer. {he strides off on stiff cavalry legs} ', '  Here, I can''t hold this little lot much longer.   ', '{clasps himself},{he strides off on stiff cavalry legs}'),
(819, 'BELLA', '{laughing} Ho ho ho ho. ', '  Ho ho ho ho. ', '{laughing}'),
(820, 'BOYLAN', '{to Bloom, over his shoulder} You can apply your eye to the keyhole and play with yourself while I just go through her a few times. ', '  You can apply your eye to the keyhole and play with yourself while I just go through her a few times. ', '{to Bloom, over his shoulder}'),
(821, 'BLOOM', 'Thank you, sir. I will, sir. May I bring two men chums to witness the deed and take a snapshot? {he holds out an ointment jar} Vaseline, sir? Orangeflower...? Lukewarm water...? ', 'Thank you, sir. I will, sir. May I bring two men chums to witness the deed and take a snapshot?   Vaseline, sir? Orangeflower...? Lukewarm water...? ', '{he holds out an ointment jar}'),
(822, 'KITTY', '{from the sofa} Tell us, Florry. Tell us. What ... {Florry whispers to her. Whispering lovewords murmur, liplapping loudly, poppysmic plopslop.} ', '  Tell us, Florry. Tell us. What ...   ', '{from the sofa},{Florry whispers to her. Whispering lovewords murmur, liplapping loudly, poppysmic plopslop.}'),
(823, 'MINA KENNEDY', '{her eyes upturned} O, it must be like the scent of geraniums and lovely peaches! O, he simply idolises every bit of her! Stuck together! Covered with kisses! ', '  O, it must be like the scent of geraniums and lovely peaches! O, he simply idolises every bit of her! Stuck together! Covered with kisses! ', '{her eyes upturned}'),
(824, 'LYDIA DOUCE', '{her mouth opening} Yumyum. O, he''s carrying her round the room doing it! Ride a cockhorse. You could hear them in Paris and New York. Like mouthfuls of strawberries and cream. ', '  Yumyum. O, he''s carrying her round the room doing it! Ride a cockhorse. You could hear them in Paris and New York. Like mouthfuls of strawberries and cream. ', '{her mouth opening}'),
(825, 'KITTY', '{laughing} Hee hee hee. ', '  Hee hee hee. ', '{laughing}'),
(826, 'BOYLAN&#8217;S VOICE', '{sweetly, hoarsely, in the pit of his stomach} Ah! Godblaze- grukbrukarchkhrasht! ', '  Ah! Godblaze- grukbrukarchkhrasht! ', '{sweetly, hoarsely, in the pit of his stomach}'),
(827, 'MARION&#8217;S VOICE', '{hoarsely, sweetly, rising to her throat} O! Weeshwashtkissinapoo- isthnapoohuck? ', '  O! Weeshwashtkissinapoo- isthnapoohuck? ', '{hoarsely, sweetly, rising to her throat}'),
(828, 'BLOOM', '{his eyes wildly dilated, clasps himself} Show! Hide! Show! Plough her! More! Shoot! ', '  Show! Hide! Show! Plough her! More! Shoot! ', '{his eyes wildly dilated, clasps himself}'),
(829, 'BELLA, ZOE, FLORRY, KITTY', 'Ho ho! Ha ha! Hee hee! ', 'Ho ho! Ha ha! Hee hee! ', ''),
(830, 'LYNCH', '{points} The mirror up to nature. {he laughs} Hu hu hu hu hu! {Stephen and Bloom gaze in the mirror. The face of William Shakespeare, beardless, appears there, rigid in facial paralysis, crowned by the reflection of the reindeer antlered hatrack in the hall.} ', '  The mirror up to nature.   Hu hu hu hu hu!   ', '{points},{he laughs},{Stephen and Bloom gaze in the mirror. The face of William Shakespeare, beardless, appears there, rigid in facial paralysis, crowned by the reflection of the reindeer antlered hatrack in the hall.}'),
(831, 'SHAKESPEARE', '{in dignified ventriloquy} ''Tis the loud laugh bespeaks the vacant mind. {to Bloom} Thou thoughtest as how thou wastest invisible. Gaze. {he crows with a black capon''s laugh} Iagogo! How my Oldfellow chokit his Thursdaymornun. Iagogogo! ', '  ''Tis the loud laugh bespeaks the vacant mind.   Thou thoughtest as how thou wastest invisible. Gaze.   Iagogo! How my Oldfellow chokit his Thursdaymornun. Iagogogo! ', '{in dignified ventriloquy},{to Bloom},{he crows with a black capon''s laugh}'),
(832, 'BLOOM', '{smiles yellowly at the three whores} When will I hear the joke? ', '  When will I hear the joke? ', '{smiles yellowly at the three whores}'),
(833, 'ZOE', 'Before you''re twice married and once a widower. ', 'Before you''re twice married and once a widower. ', ''),
(834, 'BLOOM', 'Lapses are condoned. Even the great Napoleon when measurements were taken next the skin after his death ... {Mrs Dignam, widow woman, her snubnose and cheeks flushed with deathtalk, tears and Tunney''s tawny sherry, hurries by in her weeds, her bonnet awry, rouging and powdering her cheeks, lips and nose, a pen chivvying her brood of cygnets. Beneath her skirt appear her late husband''s everyday trousers and turnedup boots, large eights. She holds a Scottish Widows'' insurance policy and a large marquee umbrella under which her brood run with her, Patsy hopping on one shod foot, his collar loose, a hank of porksteaks dangling, Freddy whimpering, Susy with a crying cod''s mouth, Alice struggling with the baby. She cuffs them on, her streamers flaunting aloft.} ', 'Lapses are condoned. Even the great Napoleon when measurements were taken next the skin after his death ...   ', '{Mrs Dignam, widow woman, her snubnose and cheeks flushed with deathtalk, tears and Tunney''s tawny sherry, hurries by in her weeds, her bonnet awry, rouging and powdering her cheeks, lips and nose, a pen chivvying her brood of cygnets. Beneath her skirt appear her late husband''s everyday trousers and turnedup boots, large eights. She holds a Scottish Widows'' insurance policy and a large marquee umbrella under which her brood run with her, Patsy hopping on one shod foot, his collar loose, a hank of porksteaks dangling, Freddy whimpering, Susy with a crying cod''s mouth, Alice struggling with the baby. She cuffs them on, her streamers flaunting aloft.}'),
(835, 'FREDDY', 'Ah, ma, you''re dragging me along! ', 'Ah, ma, you''re dragging me along! ', ''),
(836, 'SUSY', 'Mamma, the beeftea is fizzing over! ', 'Mamma, the beeftea is fizzing over! ', ''),
(837, 'SHAKESPEARE', '{with paralytic rage} Weda seca whokilla farst. {The face of Martin Cunningham, bearded, refeatures Shakespeare''s beardless face. The marquee umbrella sways drunkenly, the children run aside. Under the umbrella appears Mrs Cunningham in merry widow hat and kimono gown. She glides sidling and bowing, twirling japanesily.} ', '  Weda seca whokilla farst.   ', '{with paralytic rage},{The face of Martin Cunningham, bearded, refeatures Shakespeare''s beardless face. The marquee umbrella sways drunkenly, the children run aside. Under the umbrella appears Mrs Cunningham in merry widow hat and kimono gown. She glides sidling and bowing, twirling japanesily.}'),
(838, 'MRS CUNNINGHAM', '{sings} And they call me the jewel of Asia! ', '  And they call me the jewel of Asia! ', '{sings}'),
(839, 'MARTIN CUNNINGHAM', '{gazes on her, impassive} Immense! Most bloody awful demirep! ', '  Immense! Most bloody awful demirep! ', '{gazes on her, impassive}'),
(840, 'STEPHEN', 'Et exaltabuntur cornua iusti. Queens lay with prize bulls. Remember Pasiphae for whose lust my grandoldgrossfather made the first confessionbox. Forget not Madam Grissel Steevens nor the suine scions of the house of Lambert. And Noah was drunk with wine. And his ark was open. ', 'Et exaltabuntur cornua iusti. Queens lay with prize bulls. Remember Pasiphae for whose lust my grandoldgrossfather made the first confessionbox. Forget not Madam Grissel Steevens nor the suine scions of the house of Lambert. And Noah was drunk with wine. And his ark was open. ', ''),
(841, 'BELLA', 'None of that here. Come to the wrong shop. ', 'None of that here. Come to the wrong shop. ', ''),
(842, 'LYNCH', 'Let him alone. He''s back from Paris. ', 'Let him alone. He''s back from Paris. ', ''),
(843, 'ZOE', '{runs to Stephen and links him} O go on! Give us some parleyvoo. {Stephen claps hat on head and leaps over to the fireplace where he stands with shrugged shoulders, finny hands outspread, a painted smile on his face.} ', '  O go on! Give us some parleyvoo.   ', '{runs to Stephen and links him},{Stephen claps hat on head and leaps over to the fireplace where he stands with shrugged shoulders, finny hands outspread, a painted smile on his face.}'),
(844, 'LYNCH', '{pommelling on the sofa} Rmm Rmm Rmm Rrrrrrmmmm. ', '  Rmm Rmm Rmm Rrrrrrmmmm. ', '{pommelling on the sofa}'),
(845, 'STEPHEN', '{gabbles with marionette jerks} Thousand places of entertainment to expense your evenings with lovely ladies saling gloves and other things perhaps hers heart beerchops perfect fashionable house very eccentric where lots cocottes beautiful dressed much about princesses like are dancing cancan and walking there parisian clowneries extra foolish for bachelors foreigns the same if talking a poor english how much smart they are on things love and sensations voluptuous. Misters very selects for is pleasure must to visit heaven and hell show with mortuary candles and they tears silver which occur every night. Perfectly shocking terrific of religion''s things mockery seen in universal world. All chic womans which arrive full of modesty then disrobe and squeal loud to see vampire man debauch nun very fresh young with dessous troublants. {he clacks his tongue loudly} Ho, là là! Ce pif qu''il a! ', '  Thousand places of entertainment to expense your evenings with lovely ladies saling gloves and other things perhaps hers heart beerchops perfect fashionable house very eccentric where lots cocottes beautiful dressed much about princesses like are dancing cancan and walking there parisian clowneries extra foolish for bachelors foreigns the same if talking a poor english how much smart they are on things love and sensations voluptuous. Misters very selects for is pleasure must to visit heaven and hell show with mortuary candles and they tears silver which occur every night. Perfectly shocking terrific of religion''s things mockery seen in universal world. All chic womans which arrive full of modesty then disrobe and squeal loud to see vampire man debauch nun very fresh young with dessous troublants.   Ho, là là! Ce pif qu''il a! ', '{gabbles with marionette jerks},{he clacks his tongue loudly}'),
(846, 'LYNCH', 'Vive le vampire! ', 'Vive le vampire! ', ''),
(847, 'THE WHORES', 'Bravo! Parleyvoo! ', 'Bravo! Parleyvoo! ', ''),
(848, 'STEPHEN', '{with head back, laughs loudly, clapping himself grimacing} Great success of laughing. Angels much prostitutes like and holy apostles big damn ruffians. Demimondaines nicely handsome sparkling of diamonds very amiable costumed. Or do you are fond better what belongs they moderns pleasure turpitude of old mans? {he points about him with grotesque gestures which Lynch and the whores reply to} Caoutchouc statue woman reversible or lifesize tompeeptom of virgins nudities very lesbic the kiss five ten times. Enter, gentleman, to see in mirror every positions trapezes all that machine there besides also if desire act awfully bestial butcher''s boy pollutes in warm veal liver or omlet on the belly pièce de Shakespeare. ', '  Great success of laughing. Angels much prostitutes like and holy apostles big damn ruffians. Demimondaines nicely handsome sparkling of diamonds very amiable costumed. Or do you are fond better what belongs they moderns pleasure turpitude of old mans?   Caoutchouc statue woman reversible or lifesize tompeeptom of virgins nudities very lesbic the kiss five ten times. Enter, gentleman, to see in mirror every positions trapezes all that machine there besides also if desire act awfully bestial butcher''s boy pollutes in warm veal liver or omlet on the belly pièce de Shakespeare. ', '{with head back, laughs loudly, clapping himself grimacing},{he points about him with grotesque gestures which Lynch and the whores reply to}'),
(849, 'BELLA', '{clapping her belly sinks back on the sofa, with a shout of laughter} An omelette on the.... Ho! ho! ho! ho!... omelette on the.... ', '  An omelette on the.... Ho! ho! ho! ho!... omelette on the.... ', '{clapping her belly sinks back on the sofa, with a shout of laughter}'),
(850, 'STEPHEN', '{mincingly} I love you, sir darling. Speak you englishman tongue for double entente cordiale. O yes, mon loup. How much cost? Waterloo. Watercloset. {he ceases suddenly and holds up a forefinger} ', '  I love you, sir darling. Speak you englishman tongue for double entente cordiale. O yes, mon loup. How much cost? Waterloo. Watercloset.   ', '{mincingly},{he ceases suddenly and holds up a forefinger}'),
(851, 'BELLA', '{laughing} Omelette.... ', '  Omelette.... ', '{laughing}'),
