(895, 'STEPHEN', 'Pas seul! {He wheels Kitty into Lynch''s arms, snatches up his ashplant from the table and takes the floor. All wheel whirl waltz twirl Bloombella Kittylynch Florryzoe jujuby women. Stephen with hat ashplant frogsplits in middle highkicks with skykicking mouth shut hand clasp part under thigh. With clang tinkle boomhammer tallyho hornblower blue green yellow flashes Toft''s cumbersome turns with hobbyhorse riders from gilded snakes dangled, bowels fandango leaping spurn soil foot and fall again.} ', 'Pas seul!   ', '{He wheels Kitty into Lynch''s arms, snatches up his ashplant from the table and takes the floor. All wheel whirl waltz twirl Bloombella Kittylynch Florryzoe jujuby women. Stephen with hat ashplant frogsplits in middle highkicks with skykicking mouth shut hand clasp part under thigh. With clang tinkle boomhammer tallyho hornblower blue green yellow flashes Toft''s cumbersome turns with hobbyhorse riders from gilded snakes dangled, bowels fandango leaping spurn soil foot and fall again.}'),
(896, 'THE PIANOLA', 'Though she''s a factory lass And wears no fancy clothes. {Closeclutched swift swifter with glareblareflare scudding they scootlootshoot lumbering by. Baraabum!} ', 'Though she''s a factory lass And wears no fancy clothes.   ', '{Closeclutched swift swifter with glareblareflare scudding they scootlootshoot lumbering by. Baraabum!}'),
(897, 'TUTTI', 'Encore! Bis! Bravo! Encore! ', 'Encore! Bis! Bravo! Encore! ', ''),
(898, 'SIMON', 'Think of your mother''s people! ', 'Think of your mother''s people! ', ''),
(899, 'STEPHEN', 'Dance of death. {Bang fresh barang bang of lacquey''s bell, horse, nag, steer, piglings, Conmee on Christass, lame crutch and leg sailor in cockboat armfolded ropepulling hitching stamp hornpipe through and through. Baraabum! On nags hogs bellhorses Gadarene swine Corny in coffin steel shark stone onehandled Nelson two trickies Frauenzimmer plumstained from pram filling bawling Gum he''s a champion. Fuseblue peer from barrel rev. evensong Love on hackney jaunt Blazes blind coddoubled bicyclers Dilly with snowcake no fancy clothes. Then in last switchback lumbering up and down bump mashtub sort of viceroy and reine relish for tublumber bumpshire rose. Baraabum!} {The couples fall aside. Stephen whirls giddily. Room whirls back. Eyes closed he totters. Red rails fly spacewards. Stars all around suns turn roundabout. Bright midges dance on walls. He stops dead.} ', 'Dance of death.     ', '{Bang fresh barang bang of lacquey''s bell, horse, nag, steer, piglings, Conmee on Christass, lame crutch and leg sailor in cockboat armfolded ropepulling hitching stamp hornpipe through and through. Baraabum! On nags hogs bellhorses Gadarene swine Corny in coffin steel shark stone onehandled Nelson two trickies Frauenzimmer plumstained from pram filling bawling Gum he''s a champion. Fuseblue peer from barrel rev. evensong Love on hackney jaunt Blazes blind coddoubled bicyclers Dilly with snowcake no fancy clothes. Then in last switchback lumbering up and down bump mashtub sort of viceroy and reine relish for tublumber bumpshire rose. Baraabum!},{The couples fall aside. Stephen whirls giddily. Room whirls back. Eyes closed he totters. Red rails fly spacewards. Stars all around suns turn roundabout. Bright midges dance on walls. He stops dead.}'),
(900, 'STEPHEN', 'Ho! {Stephen''s mother, emaciated, rises stark through the floor, in leper grey with a wreath of faded orangeblossoms and a torn bridal veil, her face worn and noseless, green with gravemould. Her hair is scant and lank. She fixes her bluecircled hollow eyesockets on Stephen and opens her toothless mouth uttering a silent word. A choir of virgins and confessors sing voicelessly.} ', 'Ho!   ', '{Stephen''s mother, emaciated, rises stark through the floor, in leper grey with a wreath of faded orangeblossoms and a torn bridal veil, her face worn and noseless, green with gravemould. Her hair is scant and lank. She fixes her bluecircled hollow eyesockets on Stephen and opens her toothless mouth uttering a silent word. A choir of virgins and confessors sing voicelessly.}'),
(901, 'THE CHOIR', 'Liliata rutilantium te confessorum .... Iubilantium te virginum ..... {From the top of a tower Buck Mulligan, in particoloured jester''s dress of puce and yellow and clown''s cap with curling bell, stands gaping at her, a smoking buttered split scone in his hand.} ', 'Liliata rutilantium te confessorum .... Iubilantium te virginum .....   ', '{From the top of a tower Buck Mulligan, in particoloured jester''s dress of puce and yellow and clown''s cap with curling bell, stands gaping at her, a smoking buttered split scone in his hand.}'),
(902, 'BUCK MULLIGAN', 'She''s beastly dead. The pity of it! Mulligan meets the afflicted mother. {he upturns his eyes} Mercurial Malachi! ', 'She''s beastly dead. The pity of it! Mulligan meets the afflicted mother.   Mercurial Malachi! ', '{he upturns his eyes}'),
(903, 'THE MOTHER', '{with the subtle smile of death''s madness} I was once the beautiful May Goulding. I am dead. ', '  I was once the beautiful May Goulding. I am dead. ', '{with the subtle smile of death''s madness}'),
(904, 'STEPHEN', '{horrorstruck} Lemur, who are you? No. What bogeyman''s trick is this? ', '  Lemur, who are you? No. What bogeyman''s trick is this? ', '{horrorstruck}'),
(905, 'BUCK MULLIGAN', '{shakes his curling capbell} The mockery of it! Kinch dogsbody killed her bitchbody. She kicked the bucket. {tears of molten butter fall from his eyes on to the scone} Our great sweet mother! Epi oinopa ponton. ', '  The mockery of it! Kinch dogsbody killed her bitchbody. She kicked the bucket.   Our great sweet mother! Epi oinopa ponton. ', '{shakes his curling capbell},{tears of molten butter fall from his eyes on to the scone}'),
(906, 'THE MOTHER', '{comes nearer, breathing upon him softly her breath of wetted ashes} All must go through it, Stephen. More women than men in the world. You too. Time will come. ', '  All must go through it, Stephen. More women than men in the world. You too. Time will come. ', '{comes nearer, breathing upon him softly her breath of wetted ashes}'),
(907, 'STEPHEN', '{choking with fright, remorse and horror} They say I killed you, mother. He offended your memory. Cancer did it, not I. Destiny. ', '  They say I killed you, mother. He offended your memory. Cancer did it, not I. Destiny. ', '{choking with fright, remorse and horror}'),
(908, 'THE MOTHER', '{a green rill of bile trickling from a side of her mouth} You sang that song to me. Love''s bitter mystery. ', '  You sang that song to me. Love''s bitter mystery. ', '{a green rill of bile trickling from a side of her mouth}'),
(909, 'STEPHEN', '{eagerly} Tell me the word, mother, if you know now. The word known to all men. ', '  Tell me the word, mother, if you know now. The word known to all men. ', '{eagerly}'),
(910, 'THE MOTHER', 'Who saved you the night you jumped into the train at Dalkey with Paddy Lee? Who had pity for you when you were sad among the strangers? Prayer is allpowerful. Prayer for the suffering souls in the Ursuline manual and forty days'' indulgence. Repent, Stephen. ', 'Who saved you the night you jumped into the train at Dalkey with Paddy Lee? Who had pity for you when you were sad among the strangers? Prayer is allpowerful. Prayer for the suffering souls in the Ursuline manual and forty days'' indulgence. Repent, Stephen. ', ''),
(911, 'STEPHEN', 'The ghoul! Hyena! ', 'The ghoul! Hyena! ', ''),
(912, 'THE MOTHER', 'I pray for you in my other world. Get Dilly to make you that boiled rice every night after your brainwork. Years and years I loved you, O, my son, my firstborn, when you lay in my womb. ', 'I pray for you in my other world. Get Dilly to make you that boiled rice every night after your brainwork. Years and years I loved you, O, my son, my firstborn, when you lay in my womb. ', ''),
(913, 'ZOE', '{fanning herself with the gratefan} I''m melting! ', '  I''m melting! ', '{fanning herself with the gratefan}'),
(914, 'FLORRY', '{points to Stephen} Look! He''s white. ', '  Look! He''s white. ', '{points to Stephen}'),
(915, 'BLOOM', '{goes to the window to open it more} Giddy. ', '  Giddy. ', '{goes to the window to open it more}'),
(916, 'THE MOTHER', '{with smouldering eyes} Repent! O, the fire of hell! ', '  Repent! O, the fire of hell! ', '{with smouldering eyes}'),
(917, 'STEPHEN', '{panting} His noncorrosive sublimate! The corpsechewer! Raw head and bloody bones. ', '  His noncorrosive sublimate! The corpsechewer! Raw head and bloody bones. ', '{panting}'),
(918, 'THE MOTHER', '{her face drawing near and nearer, sending out an ashen breath} Beware! {she raises her blackened withered right arm slowly towards Stephen''s breast with outstretched finger} Beware God''s hand! {A green crab with malignant red eyes sticks deep its grinning claws in Stephen''s heart.} ', '  Beware!   Beware God''s hand!   ', '{her face drawing near and nearer, sending out an ashen breath},{she raises her blackened withered right arm slowly towards Stephen''s breast with outstretched finger},{A green crab with malignant red eyes sticks deep its grinning claws in Stephen''s heart.}'),
(919, 'STEPHEN', '{strangled with rage, his features drawn grey and old} Shite! ', '  Shite! ', '{strangled with rage, his features drawn grey and old}'),
(920, 'BLOOM', '{at the window} What? ', '  What? ', '{at the window}'),
(921, 'STEPHEN', 'Ah non, par exemple! The intellectual imagination! With me all or not at all. Non serviam! ', 'Ah non, par exemple! The intellectual imagination! With me all or not at all. Non serviam! ', ''),
(922, 'FLORRY', 'Give him some cold water. Wait. {she rushes out} ', 'Give him some cold water. Wait.   ', '{she rushes out}'),
(923, 'THE MOTHER', '{wrings her hands slowly, moaning desperately} O Sacred Heart of Jesus, have mercy on him! Save him from hell, O Divine Sacred Heart! ', '  O Sacred Heart of Jesus, have mercy on him! Save him from hell, O Divine Sacred Heart! ', '{wrings her hands slowly, moaning desperately}'),
(924, 'STEPHEN', 'No! No! No! Break my spirit, all of you, if you can! I''ll bring you all to heel! ', 'No! No! No! Break my spirit, all of you, if you can! I''ll bring you all to heel! ', ''),
(925, 'THE MOTHER', '{in the agony of her deathrattle} Have mercy on Stephen, Lord, for my sake! Inexpressible was my anguish when expiring with love, grief and agony on Mount Calvary. ', '  Have mercy on Stephen, Lord, for my sake! Inexpressible was my anguish when expiring with love, grief and agony on Mount Calvary. ', '{in the agony of her deathrattle}'),
(926, 'STEPHEN', 'Nothung! {He lifts his ashplant high with both hands and smashes the chandelier. Time''s livid final flame leaps and, in the following darkness, ruin of all space, shattered glass and toppling masonry.} ', 'Nothung!   ', '{He lifts his ashplant high with both hands and smashes the chandelier. Time''s livid final flame leaps and, in the following darkness, ruin of all space, shattered glass and toppling masonry.}'),
(927, 'THE GASJET', 'Pwfungg! ', 'Pwfungg! ', ''),
(928, 'BLOOM', 'Stop! ', 'Stop! ', ''),
(929, 'LYNCH', '{rushes forward and seizes Stephen''s hand} Here! Hold on! Don''t run amok! ', '  Here! Hold on! Don''t run amok! ', '{rushes forward and seizes Stephen''s hand}'),
(930, 'BELLA', 'Police! {Stephen, abandoning his ashplant, his head and arms thrown back stark, beats the ground and flies from the room, past the whores at the door.} ', 'Police!   ', '{Stephen, abandoning his ashplant, his head and arms thrown back stark, beats the ground and flies from the room, past the whores at the door.}'),
(931, 'BELLA', '{screams} After him! {The two whores rush to the halldoor. Lynch and Kitty and Zoe stampede from the room. They talk excitedly. Bloom follows, returns.} ', '  After him!   ', '{screams},{The two whores rush to the halldoor. Lynch and Kitty and Zoe stampede from the room. They talk excitedly. Bloom follows, returns.}'),
(932, 'THE WHORES', '{jammed in the doorway, pointing} Down there. ', '  Down there. ', '{jammed in the doorway, pointing}'),
(933, 'ZOE', '{pointing} There. There''s something up. ', '  There. There''s something up. ', '{pointing}'),
(934, 'BELLA', 'Who pays for the lamp? {she seizes Bloom''s coattail} Here, you were with him. The lamp''s broken. ', 'Who pays for the lamp?   Here, you were with him. The lamp''s broken. ', '{she seizes Bloom''s coattail}'),
(935, 'BLOOM', '{rushes to the hall, rushes back} What lamp, woman? ', '  What lamp, woman? ', '{rushes to the hall, rushes back}'),
(936, 'A WHORE', 'He tore his coat. ', 'He tore his coat. ', ''),
(937, 'BELLA', '{her eyes hard with anger and cupidity, points} Who''s to pay for that? Ten shillings. You''re a witness. ', '  Who''s to pay for that? Ten shillings. You''re a witness. ', '{her eyes hard with anger and cupidity, points}'),
(938, 'BLOOM', '{snatches up Stephen''s ashplant} Me? Ten shillings? Haven''t you lifted enough off him? Didn''t he ....? ', '  Me? Ten shillings? Haven''t you lifted enough off him? Didn''t he ....? ', '{snatches up Stephen''s ashplant}'),
(939, 'BELLA', '{loudly} Here, none of your tall talk. This isn''t a brothel. A tenshilling house. ', '  Here, none of your tall talk. This isn''t a brothel. A tenshilling house. ', '{loudly}'),
(940, 'BLOOM', '{His head under the lamp, pulls the chain. Puling, the gasjet lights up a crushed mauve purple shade. He raises the ashplant.} Only the chimney''s broken. Here is all he .... ', '  Only the chimney''s broken. Here is all he .... ', '{His head under the lamp, pulls the chain. Puling, the gasjet lights up a crushed mauve purple shade. He raises the ashplant.}'),
(941, 'BELLA', '{shrinks back and screams} Jesus! Don''t! ', '  Jesus! Don''t! ', '{shrinks back and screams}'),
(942, 'BLOOM', '{warding off a blow} To show you how he hit the paper. There''s not sixpenceworth of damage done. Ten shillings! ', '  To show you how he hit the paper. There''s not sixpenceworth of damage done. Ten shillings! ', '{warding off a blow}'),
(943, 'FLORRY', '{with a glass of water, enters} Where is he? ', '  Where is he? ', '{with a glass of water, enters}'),
(944, 'BELLA', 'Do you want me to call the police? ', 'Do you want me to call the police? ', ''),
(945, 'BLOOM', 'O, I know. Bulldog on the premises. But he''s a Trinity student. Patrons of your establishment. Gentlemen that pay the rent. {he makes a masonic sign} Know what I mean? Nephew of the vicechancellor. You don''t want a scandal. ', 'O, I know. Bulldog on the premises. But he''s a Trinity student. Patrons of your establishment. Gentlemen that pay the rent.   Know what I mean? Nephew of the vicechancellor. You don''t want a scandal. ', '{he makes a masonic sign}'),
(946, 'BELLA', '{angrily} Trinity. Coming down here ragging after the boatraces and paying nothing. Are you my commander here or? Where is he? I''ll charge him! Disgrace him, I will! {she shouts} Zoe! Zoe! ', '  Trinity. Coming down here ragging after the boatraces and paying nothing. Are you my commander here or? Where is he? I''ll charge him! Disgrace him, I will!   Zoe! Zoe! ', '{angrily},{she shouts}'),
(947, 'BLOOM', '{urgently} And if it were your own son in Oxford? {warningly} I know. ', '  And if it were your own son in Oxford?   I know. ', '{urgently},{warningly}'),
(948, 'BELLA', '{almost speechless} Who are. Incog! ', '  Who are. Incog! ', '{almost speechless}'),
(949, 'ZOE', '{in the doorway} There''s a row on. ', '  There''s a row on. ', '{in the doorway}'),
(950, 'BLOOM', 'What? Where? {he throws a shilling on the table and starts} That''s for the chimney. Where? I need mountain air. {He hurries out through the hall. The whores point. Florry follows, spilling water from her tilted tumbler. On the doorstep all the whores clustered talk volubly, pointing to the right where the fog has cleared off. From the left arrives a jingling hackney car. It slows to in front of the house. Bloom at the halldoor perceives Corny Kelleher who is about to dismount from the car with two silent lechers. He averts his face. Bella from within the hall urges on her whores. They blow ickylickysticky yumyum kisses. Corny Kelleher replies with a ghastly lewd smile. The silent lechers turn to pay the jarvey. Zoe and Kitty still point right. Bloom, parting them swiftly, draws his caliph''s hood and poncho and hurries down the steps with sideways face. Incog Haroun Al Raschid he flits behind the silent lechers and hastens on by the railings with fleet step of a pard strewing the drag behind him, torn envelopes drenched in aniseed. The ashplant marks his stride. A pack of bloodhounds, led by Hornblower of Trinity brandishing a dogwhip in tallyho cap and an old pair of grey trousers, follow from far, picking up the scent, nearer, baying, panting, at fault, breaking away, throwing their tongues, biting his heels, leaping at his tail. He walks, runs, zigzags, gallops, lugs laid back. He is pelted with gravel, cabbagestumps, biscuitboxes, eggs, potatoes, dead codfish, woman''s slipperslappers. After him freshfound the hue and cry zigzag gallops in hot pursuit of follow my leader: 65 C, 66 C, night watch, John Henry Menton, Wisdom Hely, VB Dillon, Councillor Nannetti, Alexander Keyes, Larry O''Rourke, Joe Cuffe, Mrs O''Dowd, Pisser Burke, the Nameless One, Mrs Riordan, the Citizen, Garryowen, Whodoyoucallhim, Strangeface, Fellowthatsolike, Sawhimbefore, Chapwithawen, Chris Callinan, sir Charles Cameron, Benjamin Dollard, Lenehan, Bartell d''Arcy, Joe Hynes, red Murray, editor Brayden, T. M. Healy, Mr Justice Fitzgibbon, John Howard Parnell, the reverend Tinned Salmon, Professor Joly, Mrs Breen, Denis Breen, Theodore Purefoy, Mina Purefoy, the Westland Row postmistress, C. P. M''Coy, friend of Lyons, Hoppy Holohan, maninthestreet, othermaninthestreet, Footballboots, pugnosed driver, rich protestant lady, Davy Byrne, Mrs Ellen M''Guinness, Mrs Joe Gallaher, George Lidwell, Jimmy Henry on corns, superintendent Laracy, Father Cowley, Crofton out of the Collector-general''s, Dan Dawson, dental surgeon Bloom with tweezers, Mrs Bob Doran, Mrs Kennefick, Mrs Wyse Nolan, John Wyse Nolan, handsomemarriedwomanrubbedagainstwidebehind- inClonskeatram, the bookseller of Sweets of Sin, Miss Dubedatandshedidbedad, Mesdames Gerald and Stanislaus Moran of Roebuck, the managing clerk of Drimmie''s, Wetherup, colonel Hayes, Mastiansky, Citron, Penrose, Aaron Figatner, Moses Herzog, Michael E Geraghty, Inspector Troy, Mrs Galbraith, the constable off Eccles street corner, old doctor Brady with stethoscope, the mystery man on the beach, a retriever, Mrs Miriam Dandrade and all her lovers.} ', 'What? Where?   That''s for the chimney. Where? I need mountain air.   ', '{he throws a shilling on the table and starts},{He hurries out through the hall. The whores point. Florry follows, spilling water from her tilted tumbler. On the doorstep all the whores clustered talk volubly, pointing to the right where the fog has cleared off. From the left arrives a jingling hackney car. It slows to in front of the house. Bloom at the halldoor perceives Corny Kelleher who is about to dismount from the car with two silent lechers. He averts his face. Bella from within the hall urges on her whores. They blow ickylickysticky yumyum kisses. Corny Kelleher replies with a ghastly lewd smile. The silent lechers turn to pay the jarvey. Zoe and Kitty still point right. Bloom, parting them swiftly, draws his caliph''s hood and poncho and hurries down the steps with