(951, 'THE HUE AND CRY', '{helterskelterpelterwelter} He''s Bloom! Stop Bloom! Stopabloom! Stopperrobber! Hi! Hi! Stophim on the corner! {At the corner of Beaver street beneath the scaffolding Bloom panting stops on the fringe of the noisy quarrelling knot, a lot not knowing a jot what hi! hi! row and wrangle round the whowhat brawlaltogether.} ', '  He''s Bloom! Stop Bloom! Stopabloom! Stopperrobber! Hi! Hi! Stophim on the corner!   ', '{helterskelterpelterwelter},{At the corner of Beaver street beneath the scaffolding Bloom panting stops on the fringe of the noisy quarrelling knot, a lot not knowing a jot what hi! hi! row and wrangle round the whowhat brawlaltogether.}'),
(952, 'STEPHEN', '{with elaborate gestures, breathing deeply and slowly} You are my guests. Uninvited. By virtue of the fifth of George and seventh of Edward. History to blame. Fabled by mothers of memory. ', '  You are my guests. Uninvited. By virtue of the fifth of George and seventh of Edward. History to blame. Fabled by mothers of memory. ', '{with elaborate gestures, breathing deeply and slowly}'),
(953, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{to Cissy Caffrey} Was he insulting you? ', '  Was he insulting you? ', '{to Cissy Caffrey}'),
(954, 'STEPHEN', 'Addressed her in vocative feminine. Probably neuter. Ungenitive. ', 'Addressed her in vocative feminine. Probably neuter. Ungenitive. ', ''),
(955, 'VOICES', 'No, he didn''t. I seen him. The girl there. He was in Mrs Cohen''s. What''s up? Soldier and civilian. ', 'No, he didn''t. I seen him. The girl there. He was in Mrs Cohen''s. What''s up? Soldier and civilian. ', ''),
(956, 'CISSY CAFFREY', 'I was in company with the soldiers and they left me to do, you know, and the young man run up behind me. But I''m faithful to the man that''s treating me though I''m only a shilling whore. ', 'I was in company with the soldiers and they left me to do, you know, and the young man run up behind me. But I''m faithful to the man that''s treating me though I''m only a shilling whore. ', ''),
(957, 'VOICES', 'She''s faithfultheman. ', 'She''s faithfultheman. ', ''),
(958, 'STEPHEN', '{catches sight of Lynch''s and Kitty''s heads} Hail, Sisyphus. {he points to himself and the others} Poetic. Uropoetic. ', '  Hail, Sisyphus.   Poetic. Uropoetic. ', '{catches sight of Lynch''s and Kitty''s heads},{he points to himself and the others}'),
(959, 'CISSY CAFFREY', 'Yes, to go with him. And me with a soldier friend. ', 'Yes, to go with him. And me with a soldier friend. ', ''),
(960, 'PRIVATE COMPTON', 'He doesn''t half want a thick ear, the blighter. Biff him one, Harry. ', 'He doesn''t half want a thick ear, the blighter. Biff him one, Harry. ', ''),
(961, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{to Cissy} Was he insulting you while me and him was having a piss? ', '  Was he insulting you while me and him was having a piss? ', '{to Cissy}'),
(962, 'LORD TENNYSON', '{gentleman poet in Union Jack blazer and cricket flannels, bareheaded, flowingbearded} Theirs not to reason why. ', '  Theirs not to reason why. ', '{gentleman poet in Union Jack blazer and cricket flannels, bareheaded, flowingbearded}'),
(963, 'PRIVATE COMPTON', 'Biff him, Harry. ', 'Biff him, Harry. ', ''),
(964, 'STEPHEN', '{to Private Compton} I don''t know your name but you are quite right. Doctor Swift says one man in armour will beat ten men in their shirts. Shirt is synechdoche. Part for the whole. ', '  I don''t know your name but you are quite right. Doctor Swift says one man in armour will beat ten men in their shirts. Shirt is synechdoche. Part for the whole. ', '{to Private Compton}'),
(965, 'CISSY CAFFREY', '{to the crowd} No, I was with the privates. ', '  No, I was with the privates. ', '{to the crowd}'),
(966, 'STEPHEN', '{amiably} Why not? The bold soldier boy. In my opinion every lady for example ..... ', '  Why not? The bold soldier boy. In my opinion every lady for example ..... ', '{amiably}'),
(967, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{his cap awry, advances to Stephen} Say, how would it be, governor, if I was to bash in your jaw? ', '  Say, how would it be, governor, if I was to bash in your jaw? ', '{his cap awry, advances to Stephen}'),
(968, 'STEPHEN', '{looks up to the sky} How? Very unpleasant. Noble art of selfpretence. Personally, I detest action. {he waves his hand} Hand hurts me slightly. Enfin ce sont vos oignons. {to Cissy Caffrey} Some trouble is on here. What is it precisely? ', '  How? Very unpleasant. Noble art of selfpretence. Personally, I detest action.   Hand hurts me slightly. Enfin ce sont vos oignons.   Some trouble is on here. What is it precisely? ', '{looks up to the sky},{he waves his hand},{to Cissy Caffrey}'),
(969, 'DOLLY GRAY', '{from her balcony waves her handkerchief, giving the sign of the heroine of Jericho} Rahab. Cook''s son, goodbye. Safe home to Dolly. Dream of the girl you left behind and she will dream of you. {The soldiers turn their swimming eyes.} ', '  Rahab. Cook''s son, goodbye. Safe home to Dolly. Dream of the girl you left behind and she will dream of you.   ', '{from her balcony waves her handkerchief, giving the sign of the heroine of Jericho},{The soldiers turn their swimming eyes.}'),
(970, 'BLOOM', '{elbowing through the crowd, plucks Stephen''s sleeve vigorously} Come now, professor, that carman is waiting. ', '  Come now, professor, that carman is waiting. ', '{elbowing through the crowd, plucks Stephen''s sleeve vigorously}'),
(971, 'STEPHEN', '{turns} Eh? {he disengages himself} Why should I not speak to him or to any human being who walks upright upon this oblate orange? {he points his finger} I''m not afraid of what I can talk to if I see his eye. Retaining the perpendicular. {he staggers a pace back} ', '  Eh?   Why should I not speak to him or to any human being who walks upright upon this oblate orange?   I''m not afraid of what I can talk to if I see his eye. Retaining the perpendicular.   ', '{turns},{he disengages himself},{he points his finger},{he staggers a pace back}'),
(972, 'BLOOM', '{propping him} Retain your own. ', '  Retain your own. ', '{propping him}'),
(973, 'STEPHEN', '{laughs emptily} My centre of gravity is displaced. I have forgotten the trick. Let us sit down somewhere and discuss. Struggle for life is the law of existence but but human philirenists, notably the tsar and the king of England, have invented arbitration. {he taps his brow} But in here it is I must kill the priest and the king. ', '  My centre of gravity is displaced. I have forgotten the trick. Let us sit down somewhere and discuss. Struggle for life is the law of existence but but human philirenists, notably the tsar and the king of England, have invented arbitration.   But in here it is I must kill the priest and the king. ', '{laughs emptily},{he taps his brow}'),
(974, 'BIDDY THE CLAP', 'Did you hear what the professor said? He''s a professor out of the college. ', 'Did you hear what the professor said? He''s a professor out of the college. ', ''),
(975, 'CUNTY KATE', 'I did. I heard that. ', 'I did. I heard that. ', ''),
(976, 'BIDDY THE CLAP', 'He expresses himself with such marked refinement of phraseology. ', 'He expresses himself with such marked refinement of phraseology. ', ''),
(977, 'CUNTY KATE', 'Indeed, yes. And at the same time with such apposite trenchancy. ', 'Indeed, yes. And at the same time with such apposite trenchancy. ', ''),
(978, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{pulls himself free and comes forward} What''s that you''re saying about my king? {Edward the Seventh appears in an archway. He wears a white jersey on which an image of the Sacred Heart is stitched with the insignia of Garter and Thistle, Golden Fleece, Elephant of Denmark, Skinner''s and Probyn''s horse, Lincoln''s Inn bencher and ancient and honourable artillery company of Massachusetts. He sucks a red jujube. He is robed as a grand elect perfect and sublime mason with trowel and apron, marked made in Germany. In his left hand he holds a plasterer''s bucket on which is printed Défense d''uriner. A roar of welcome greets him.} ', '  What''s that you''re saying about my king? {Edward the Seventh appears in an archway. He wears a white jersey on which an image of the Sacred Heart is stitched with the insignia of Garter and Thistle, Golden Fleece, Elephant of Denmark, Skinner''s and Probyn''s horse, Lincoln''s Inn bencher and ancient and honourable artillery company of Massachusetts. He sucks a red jujube. He is robed as a grand elect perfect and sublime mason with trowel and apron, marked made in Germany. In his left hand he holds a plasterer''s bucket on which is printed Défense d''uriner. A roar of welcome greets him.} ', '{pulls himself free and comes forward}'),
(979, 'EDWARD THE SEVENTH', '{slowly, solemnly but indistinctly} Peace, perfect peace. For identification, bucket in my hand. Cheerio, boys. {he turns to his subjects} We have come here to witness a clean straight fight and we heartily wish both men the best of good luck. Mahak makar a bak. {he shakes hands with Private Carr, Private Compton, Stephen, Bloom and Lynch} {General applause. Edward the Seventh lifts his bucket graciously in acknowledgment.} ', '  Peace, perfect peace. For identification, bucket in my hand. Cheerio, boys.   We have come here to witness a clean straight fight and we heartily wish both men the best of good luck. Mahak makar a bak.     ', '{slowly, solemnly but indistinctly},{he turns to his subjects},{he shakes hands with Private Carr, Private Compton, Stephen, Bloom and Lynch},{General applause. Edward the Seventh lifts his bucket graciously in acknowledgment.}'),
(980, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{to Stephen} Say it again. ', '  Say it again. ', '{to Stephen}'),
(981, 'STEPHEN', '{nervous, friendly, pulls himself up} I understand your point of view though I have no king myself for the moment. This is the age of patent medicines. A discussion is difficult down here. But this is the point. You die for your country. Suppose. {he places his arm on Private Carr''s sleeve} Not that I wish it for you. But I say: Let my country die for me. Up to the present it has done so. I didn''t want it to die. Damn death. Long live life! ', '  I understand your point of view though I have no king myself for the moment. This is the age of patent medicines. A discussion is difficult down here. But this is the point. You die for your country. Suppose.   Not that I wish it for you. But I say: Let my country die for me. Up to the present it has done so. I didn''t want it to die. Damn death. Long live life! ', '{nervous, friendly, pulls himself up},{he places his arm on Private Carr''s sleeve}'),
(982, 'EDWARD THE SEVENTH', '{levitates over heaps of slain, in the garb and with the halo of Joking Jesus, a white jujube in his phosphorescent face} My methods are new and are causing surprise. To make the blind see I throw dust in their eyes. ', '  My methods are new and are causing surprise. To make the blind see I throw dust in their eyes. ', '{levitates over heaps of slain, in the garb and with the halo of Joking Jesus, a white jujube in his phosphorescent face}'),
(983, 'STEPHEN', 'Kings and unicorns! {he fills back a pace} Come somewhere and we''ll... What was that girl saying ...? ', 'Kings and unicorns!   Come somewhere and we''ll... What was that girl saying ...? ', '{he fills back a pace}'),
(984, 'PRIVATE COMPTON', 'Eh, Harry, give him a kick in the knackers. Stick one into Jerry. ', 'Eh, Harry, give him a kick in the knackers. Stick one into Jerry. ', ''),
(985, 'BLOOM', '{to the privates, softly} He doesn''t know what he''s saying. Taken a little more than is good for him. Absinthe. Greeneyed monster. I know him. He''s a gentleman, a poet. It''s all right. ', '  He doesn''t know what he''s saying. Taken a little more than is good for him. Absinthe. Greeneyed monster. I know him. He''s a gentleman, a poet. It''s all right. ', '{to the privates, softly}'),
(986, 'STEPHEN', '{nods, smiling and laughing} Gentleman, patriot, scholar and judge of impostors. ', '  Gentleman, patriot, scholar and judge of impostors. ', '{nods, smiling and laughing}'),
(987, 'PRIVATE CARR', 'I don''t give a bugger who he is. ', 'I don''t give a bugger who he is. ', ''),
(988, 'PRIVATE COMPTON', 'We don''t give a bugger who he is. ', 'We don''t give a bugger who he is. ', ''),
(989, 'STEPHEN', 'I seem to annoy them. Green rag to a bull. {Kevin Egan of Paris in black Spanish tasselled shirt and peep-o''-day boy''s hat signs to Stephen.} ', 'I seem to annoy them. Green rag to a bull.   ', '{Kevin Egan of Paris in black Spanish tasselled shirt and peep-o''-day boy''s hat signs to Stephen.}'),
(990, 'KEVIN EGAN', 'H''lo! Bonjour! The vieille ogresse with the dents jaunes. {Patrice Egan peeps from behind, his rabbitface nibbling a quince leaf.} ', 'H''lo! Bonjour! The vieille ogresse with the dents jaunes.   ', '{Patrice Egan peeps from behind, his rabbitface nibbling a quince leaf.}'),
(991, 'PATRICE', 'Socialiste! ', 'Socialiste! ', ''),
(992, 'DON EMILE PATRIZIO FRANZ RUPERT POPE HENNESSY', '{in medieval hauberk, two wild geese volant on his helm, with noble indignation points a mailed hand against the privates} Werf those eykes to footboden, big grand porcos of johnyellows todos covered of gravy! ', '  Werf those eykes to footboden, big grand porcos of johnyellows todos covered of gravy! ', '{in medieval hauberk, two wild geese volant on his helm, with noble indignation points a mailed hand against the privates}'),
(993, 'BLOOM', '{to Stephen} Come home. You''ll get into trouble. ', '  Come home. You''ll get into trouble. ', '{to Stephen}'),
(994, 'STEPHEN', '{swaying} I don''t avoid it. He provokes my intelligence. ', '  I don''t avoid it. He provokes my intelligence. ', '{swaying}'),
(995, 'BIDDY THE CLAP', 'One immediately observes that he is of patrician lineage. ', 'One immediately observes that he is of patrician lineage. ', ''),
(996, 'THE VIRAGO', 'Green above the red, says he. Wolfe Tone. ', 'Green above the red, says he. Wolfe Tone. ', ''),
(997, 'THE BAWD', 'The red''s as good as the green. And better. Up the soldiers! Up King Edward! ', 'The red''s as good as the green. And better. Up the soldiers! Up King Edward! ', ''),
(998, 'A ROUGH', '{laughs} Ay! Hands up to De Wet. ', '  Ay! Hands up to De Wet. ', '{laughs}'),
(999, 'THE CITIZEN', '{with a huge emerald muffler and shillelagh, calls} May the God above Send down a dove With teeth as sharp as razors To slit the throats Of the English dogs That hanged our Irish leaders. ', '  May the God above Send down a dove With teeth as sharp as razors To slit the throats Of the English dogs That hanged our Irish leaders. ', '{with a huge emerald muffler and shillelagh, calls}'),
(1000, 'THE CROPPY BOY', '{the ropenoose round his neck, gripes in his issuing bowels with both hands} I bear no hate to a living thing, But I love my country beyond the king. ', '  I bear no hate to a living thing, But I love my country beyond the king. ', '{the ropenoose round his neck, gripes in his issuing bowels with both hands}'),
(1001, 'RUMBOLD, DEMON BARBER', '{accompanied by two blackmasked assistants, advances with gladstone bag which he opens} Ladies and gents, cleaver purchased by Mrs Pearcy to slay Mogg. Knife with which Voisin dismembered the wife of a compatriot and hid remains in a sheet in the cellar, the unfortunate female''s throat being cut from ear to ear. Phial containing arsenic retrieved from body of Miss Barron which sent Seddon to the gallows. {He jerks the rope. The assistants leap at the victim''s legs and drag him downward, grunting. The croppy boy''s tongue protrudes violently.} ', '  Ladies and gents, cleaver purchased by Mrs Pearcy to slay Mogg. Knife with which Voisin dismembered the wife of a compatriot and hid remains in a sheet in the cellar, the unfortunate female''s throat being cut from ear to ear. Phial containing arsenic retrieved from body of Miss Barron which sent Seddon to the gallows.   ', '{accompanied by two blackmasked assistants, advances with gladstone bag which he opens},{He jerks the rope. The assistants leap at the victim''s legs and drag him downward, grunting. The croppy boy''s tongue protrudes violently.}'),
(1002, 'THE CROPPY BOY', 'Horhot ho hray hor hother''s hest. {He gives up the ghost. A violent erection of the hanged sends gouts of sperm spouting through his deathclothes on to the cobblestones. Mrs Bellingham, Mrs Yelverton Barry and the Honourable Mrs Mervyn Talboys rush forward with their handkerchiefs to sop it up.} ', 'Horhot ho hray hor hother''s hest.   ', '{He gives up the ghost. A violent erection of the hanged sends gouts of sperm spouting through his deathclothes on to the cobblestones. Mrs Bellingham, Mrs Yelverton Barry and the Honourable Mrs Mervyn Talboys rush forward with their handkerchiefs to sop it up.}'),
(1003, 'RUMBOLD', 'I''m near it myself. {he undoes the noose} Rope which hanged the awful rebel. Ten shillings a time. As applied to Her Royal Highness. {he plunges his head into the gaping belly of the hanged and draws out his head again clotted with coiled and smoking entrails} My painful duty has now been done. God save the king! ', 'I''m near it myself.   Rope which hanged the awful rebel. Ten shillings a time. As applied to Her Royal Highness.   My painful duty has now been done. God save the king! ', '{he undoes the noose},{he plunges his head into the gaping belly of the hanged and draws out his head again clotted with coiled and smoking entrails}'),
(1004, 'EDWARD THE SEVENTH', '{dances slowly, solemnly, rattling his bucket, and sings with soft contentment} On coronation day, on coronation day, O, won''t we have a merry time, Drinking whisky, beer and wine! ', '  On coronation day, on coronation day, O, won''t we have a merry time, Drinking whisky, beer and wine! ', '{dances slowly, solemnly, rattling his bucket, and sings with soft contentment}'),
(1005, 'PRIVATE CARR', 'Here. What are you saying about my king? ', 'Here. What are you saying about my king? ', ''),
(1006, 'STEPHEN', '{throws up his hands} O, this is too monotonous! Nothing. He wants my money and my life, though want must be his master, for some brutish empire of his. Money I haven''t. {he searches his pockets vaguely} Gave it to someone. ', '  O, this is too monotonous! Nothing. He wants my money and my life, though want must be his master, for some brutish empire of his. Money I haven''t.   Gave it to someone. ', '{throws up his hands},{he searches his pockets vaguely}'),
(1007, 'PRIVATE CARR', 'Who wants your bleeding money? ', 'Who wants your bleeding money? ', ''),
(1008, 'STEPHEN', '{tries to move off} Will someone tell me where I am least likely to meet these necessary evils? ça se voit aussi à Paris. Not that I ... But, by saint Patrick ....! {The women''s heads coalesce. Old Gummy Granny in sugarloaf hat appears seated on a toadstool, the deathflower of the potato blight on her breast.} ', '  Will someone tell me where I am least likely to meet these necessary evils? ça se voit aussi à Paris. Not that I ... But, by saint Patrick ....!   ', '{tries to move off},{The women''s heads coalesce. Old Gummy Granny in sugarloaf hat appears seated on a toadstool, the deathflower of the potato blight on her breast.}'),
(1009, 'STEPHEN', 'Aha! I know you, gammer! Hamlet, revenge! The old sow that eats her farrow! ', 'Aha! I know you, gammer! Hamlet, revenge! The old sow that eats her farrow! ', ''),
(1010, 'OLD GUMMY GRANNY', '{rocking to and fro} Ireland''s sweetheart, the king of Spain''s daughter, alanna. Strangers in my house, bad manners to them! {she keens with banshee woe} Ochone! Ochone! Silk of the kine! {she wails} You met with poor old Ireland and how does she stand? ', '  Ireland''s sweetheart, the king of Spain''s daughter, alanna. Strangers in my house, bad manners to them!   Ochone! Ochone! Silk of the kine!   You met with poor old Ireland and how does she stand? ', '{rocking to and fro},{she keens with banshee woe},{she wails}'),
(1011, 'STEPHEN', 'How do I stand you? The hat trick! Where''s the third person of the Blessed Trinity? Soggarth Aroon? The reverend Carrion Crow. ', 'How do I stand you? The hat trick! Where''s the third person of the Blessed Trinity? Soggarth Aroon? The reverend Carrion Crow. ', ''),
(1012, 'CISSY CAFFREY', '{shrill} Stop them from fighting! ', '  Stop them from fighting! ', '{shrill}'),
(1013, 'A ROUGH', 'Our men retreated. ', 'Our men retreated. ', ''),
(1014, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{tugging at his belt} I''ll wring the neck of any fucker says a word against my fucking king. ', '  I''ll wring the neck of any fucker says a word against my fucking king. ', '{tugging at his belt}'),
(1015, 'BLOOM', '{terrified} He said nothing. Not a word. A pure misunderstanding. ', '  He said nothing. Not a word. A pure misunderstanding. ', '{terrified}'),
(1016, 'PRIVATE COMPTON', 'Go it, Harry. Do him one in the eye. He''s a proBoer. ', 'Go it, Harry. Do him one in the eye. He''s a proBoer. ', ''),
(1017, 'STEPHEN', 'Did I? When? ', 'Did I? When? ', ''),
(1018, 'BLOOM', '{to the redcoats} We fought for you in South Africa, Irish missile troops. Isn''t that history? Royal Dublin Fusiliers. Honoured by our monarch. ', '  We fought for you in South Africa, Irish missile troops. Isn''t that history? Royal Dublin Fusiliers. Honoured by our monarch. ', '{to the redcoats}'),
(1019, 'THE NAVVY', '{staggering past} O, yes! O God, yes! O, make the kwawr a krowawr! O! Bo! {Casqued halberdiers in armour thrust forward a pentice of gutted spearpoints. Major Tweedy, moustached like Turko the terrible, in bearskin cap with hackleplume and accoutrements, with epaulettes, gilt chevrons and sabretaches, his breast bright with medals, toes the line. He gives the pilgrim warrior''s sign of the knights templars.} ', '  O, yes! O God, yes! O, make the kwawr a krowawr! O! Bo!   ', '{staggering past},{Casqued halberdiers in armour thrust forward a pentice of gutted spearpoints. Major Tweedy, moustached like Turko the terrible, in bearskin cap with hackleplume and accoutrements, with epaulettes, gilt chevrons and sabretaches, his breast bright with medals, toes the line. He gives the pilgrim warrior''s sign of the knights templars.}'),
(1020, 'MAJOR TWEEDY', '{growls gruffly} Rorke''s Drift! Up, guards, and at them! Mahar shalal hashbaz. ', '  Rorke''s Drift! Up, guards, and at them! Mahar shalal hashbaz. ', '{growls gruffly}'),
(1021, 'THE CITIZEN', 'Erin go bragh! {Major Tweedy and the Citizen exhibit to each other medals, decorations, trophies of war, wounds. Both salute with fierce hostility.} ', 'Erin go bragh!   ', '{Major Tweedy and the Citizen exhibit to each other medals, decorations, trophies of war, wounds. Both salute with fierce hostility.}'),
(1022, 'PRIVATE CARR', 'I''ll do him in. ', 'I''ll do him in. ', ''),
(1023, 'PRIVATE COMPTON', '{waves the crowd back} Fair play, here. Make a bleeding butcher''s shop of the bugger. {Massed bands blare Garryowen and God save the king.} ', '  Fair play, here. Make a bleeding butcher''s shop of the bugger.   ', '{waves the crowd back},{Massed bands blare Garryowen and God save the king.}'),
(1024, 'CISSY CAFFREY', 'They''re going to fight. For me! ', 'They''re going to fight. For me! ', ''),
(1025, 'CUNTY KATE', 'The brave and the fair. ', 'The brave and the fair. ', ''),
(1026, 'BIDDY THE CLAP', 'Methinks yon sable knight will joust it with the best. ', 'Methinks yon sable knight will joust it with the best. ', ''),
(1027, 'CUNTY KATE', '{blushing deeply} Nay, madam. The gules doublet and merry saint George for me! ', '  Nay, madam. The gules doublet and merry saint George for me! ', '{blushing deeply}'),
(1028, 'STEPHEN', 'The harlot''s cry from street to street Shall weave Old Ireland''s windingsheet. ', 'The harlot''s cry from street to street Shall weave Old Ireland''s windingsheet. ', ''),
(1029, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{loosening his belt, shouts} I''ll wring the neck of any fucking bastard says a word against my bleeding fucking king. ', '  I''ll wring the neck of any fucking bastard says a word against my bleeding fucking king. ', '{loosening his belt, shouts}'),
(1030, 'BLOOM', '{shakes Cissy Caffrey''s shoulders} Speak, you! Are you struck dumb? You are the link between nations and generations. Speak, woman, sacred lifegiver! ', '  Speak, you! Are you struck dumb? You are the link between nations and generations. Speak, woman, sacred lifegiver! ', '{shakes Cissy Caffrey''s shoulders}'),
(1031, 'CISSY CAFFREY', '{alarmed, seizes Private Carr''s sleeve} Amn''t I with you? Amn''t I your girl? Cissy''s your girl. {she cries} Police! ', '  Amn''t I with you? Amn''t I your girl? Cissy''s your girl.   Police! ', '{alarmed, seizes Private Carr''s sleeve},{she cries}'),
(1032, 'STEPHEN', '{ecstatically, to Cissy Caffrey} White thy fambles, red thy gan And thy quarrons dainty is. ', '  White thy fambles, red thy gan And thy quarrons dainty is. ', '{ecstatically, to Cissy Caffrey}'),
(1033, 'VOICES', 'Police! ', 'Police! ', '');
INSERT INTO `circe` (`id`, `speaker`, `full`, `spoken`, `directions`) VALUES
(1034, 'DISTANT VOICES', 'Dublin''s burning! Dublin''s burning! On fire, on fire! {Brimstone fires spring up. Dense clouds roll past. Heavy Gatling guns boom. Pandemonium. Troops deploy. Gallop of hoofs. Artillery. Hoarse commands. Bells clang. Backers shout. Drunkards bawl. Whores screech. Foghorns hoot. Cries of valour. Shrieks of dying. Pikes clash on cuirasses. Thieves rob the slain. Birds of prey, winging from the sea, rising from marshlands, swooping from eyries, hover screaming, gannets, cormorants, vultures, goshawks, climbing woodcocks, peregrines, merlins, blackgrouse, sea eagles, gulls, albatrosses, barnacle geese. The midnight sun is darkened. The earth trembles. The dead of Dublin from Prospect and Mount Jerome in white sheepskin overcoats and black goatfell cloaks arise and appear to many. A chasm opens with a noiseless yawn. Tom Rochford, winner, in athlete''s singlet and breeches, arrives at the head of the national hurdle handicap and leaps into the void. He is followed by a race of runners and leapers. In wild attitudes they spring from the brink. Their bodies plunge. Factory lasses with fancy clothes toss redhot Yorkshire baraabombs. Society ladies lift their skirts above their heads to protect themselves. Laughing witches in red cutty sarks ride through the air on broomsticks. Quakerlyster plasters blisters. It rains dragons'' teeth. Armed heroes spring up from furrows. They exchange in amity the pass of knights of the red cross and fight duels with cavalry sabres: Wolfe Tone against Henry Grattan, Smith O''Brien against Daniel O''Connell, Michael Davitt against Isaac Butt, Justin M''Carthy against Parnell, Arthur Griffith against John Redmond, John O''Leary against Lear O''Johnny, Lord Edward Fitzgerald against Lord Gerald Fitzedward, The O''Donoghue of The Glens against The Glens of The O''Donoghue. On an eminence, the centre of the earth, rises the feldaltar of Saint Barbara. Black candles rise from its gospel and epistle horns. From the high barbacans of the tower two shafts of light fall on the smokepalled altarstone. On the altarstone Mrs Mina Purefoy, goddess of unreason, lies, naked, fettered, a chalice resting on her swollen belly. Father Malachi O''Flynn in a lace petticoat and reversed chasuble, his two left feet back to the front, celebrates camp mass. The Reverend Mr Hugh C Haines Love M. A. in a plain cassock and mortarboard, his head and collar back to the front, holds over the celebrant''s head an open umbrella.} ', 'Dublin''s burning! Dublin''s burning! On fire, on fire!   ', '{Brimstone fires spring up. Dense clouds roll past. Heavy Gatling guns boom. Pandemonium. Troops deploy. Gallop of hoofs. Artillery. Hoarse commands. Bells clang. Backers shout. Drunkards bawl. Whores screech. Foghorns hoot. Cries of valour. Shrieks of dying. Pikes clash on cuirasses. Thieves rob the slain. Birds of prey, winging from the sea, rising from marshlands, swooping from eyries, hover screaming, gannets, cormorants, vultures, goshawks, climbing woodcocks, peregrines, merlins, blackgrouse, sea eagles, gulls, albatrosses, barnacle geese. The midnight sun is darkened. The earth trembles. The dead of Dublin from Prospect and Mount Jerome in white sheepskin overcoats and black goatfell cloaks arise and appear to many. A chasm opens with a noiseless yawn. Tom Rochford, winner, in athlete''s singlet and breeches, arrives at the head of the national hurdle handicap and leaps into the void. He is followed by a race of runners and leapers. In wild attitudes they spring from the brink. Their bodies plunge. Factory lasses with fancy clothes toss redhot Yorkshire baraabombs. Society ladies lift their skirts above their heads to protect themselves. Laughing witches in red cutty sarks ride through the air on broomsticks. Quakerlyster plasters blisters. It rains dragons'' teeth. Armed heroes spring up from furrows. They exchange in amity the pass of knights of the red cross and fight duels with cavalry sabres: Wolfe Tone against Henry Grattan, Smith O''Brien against Daniel O''Connell, Michael Davitt against Isaac Butt, Justin M''Carthy against Parnell, Arthur Griffith against John Redmond, John O''Leary against Lear O''Johnny, Lord Edward Fitzgerald against Lord Gerald Fitzedward, The O''Donoghue of The Glens against The Glens of The O''Donoghue. On an eminence, the centre of the earth, rises the feldaltar of Saint Barbara. Black candles rise from its gospel and epistle horns. From the high barbacans of the tower two shafts of light fall on the smokepalled altarstone. On the altarstone Mrs Mina Purefoy, goddess of unreason, lies, naked, fettered, a chalice resting on her swollen belly. Father Malachi O''Flynn in a lace petticoat and reversed chasuble, his two left feet back to the front, celebrates camp mass. The Reverend Mr Hugh C Haines Love M. A. in a plain cassock and mortarboard, his head and collar back to the front, holds over the celebrant''s head an open umbrella.}'),
(1035, 'FATHER MALACHI O&#8217;FLYNN', 'Introibo ad altare diaboli. ', 'Introibo ad altare diaboli. ', ''),
(1036, 'THE REVEREND MR HAINES LOVE', 'To the devil which hath made glad my young days. ', 'To the devil which hath made glad my young days. ', ''),
(1037, 'FATHER MALACHI O&#8217;FLYNN', '{takes from the chalice and elevates a blooddripping host} Corpus meum. ', '  Corpus meum. ', '{takes from the chalice and elevates a blooddripping host}'),
(1038, 'THE REVEREND MR HAINES LOVE', '{raises high behind the celebrant''s petticoat, revealing his grey bare hairy buttocks between which a carrot is stuck} My body. ', '  My body. ', '{raises high behind the celebrant''s petticoat, revealing his grey bare hairy buttocks between which a carrot is stuck}'),
(1039, 'THE VOICE OF ALL THE DAMNED', 'Htengier Tnetopinmo Dog Drol eht rof, Aiulella! {From on high the voice of Adonai calls.} ', 'Htengier Tnetopinmo Dog Drol eht rof, Aiulella!   ', '{From on high the voice of Adonai calls.}'),
(1040, 'ADONAI', 'Dooooooooooog! ', 'Dooooooooooog! ', ''),
(1041, 'THE VOICE OF ALL THE BLESSED', 'Alleluia, for the Lord God Omnipotent reigneth! {From on high the voice of Adonai calls.} ', 'Alleluia, for the Lord God Omnipotent reigneth!   ', '{From on high the voice of Adonai calls.}'),
(1042, 'ADONAI', 'Goooooooooood! {In strident discord peasants and townsmen of Orange and Green factions sing Kick the Pope and Daily, daily sing to Mary.} ', 'Goooooooooood!   ', '{In strident discord peasants and townsmen of Orange and Green factions sing Kick the Pope and Daily, daily sing to Mary.}'),
(1043, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{with ferocious articulation} I''ll do him in, so help me fucking Christ! I''ll wring the bastard fucker''s bleeding blasted fucking windpipe! {The retriever, nosing on the fringe of the crowd, barks noisily.} ', '  I''ll do him in, so help me fucking Christ! I''ll wring the bastard fucker''s bleeding blasted fucking windpipe!   ', '{with ferocious articulation},{The retriever, nosing on the fringe of the crowd, barks noisily.}'),
(1044, 'BLOOM', '{runs to Lynch} Can''t you get him away? ', '  Can''t you get him away? ', '{runs to Lynch}'),
(1045, 'LYNCH', 'He likes dialectic, the universal language. Kitty! {to Bloom} Get him away, you. He won''t listen to me. {He drags Kitty away.} ', 'He likes dialectic, the universal language. Kitty!   Get him away, you. He won''t listen to me.   ', '{to Bloom},{He drags Kitty away.}'),
(1046, 'STEPHEN', '{points} Exit Judas. Et laqueo se suspendit. ', '  Exit Judas. Et laqueo se suspendit. ', '{points}'),
(1047, 'BLOOM', '{runs to Stephen} Come along with me now before worse happens. Here''s your stick. ', '  Come along with me now before worse happens. Here''s your stick. ', '{runs to Stephen}'),
(1048, 'STEPHEN', 'Stick, no. Reason. This feast of pure reason. ', 'Stick, no. Reason. This feast of pure reason. ', ''),
(1049, 'OLD GUMMY GRANNY', '{thrusts a dagger towards Stephen''s hand} Remove him, acushla. At 8.35 a.m. you will be in heaven and Ireland will be free. {she prays} O good God, take him! ', '  Remove him, acushla. At 8.35 a.m. you will be in heaven and Ireland will be free.   O good God, take him! ', '{thrusts a dagger towards Stephen''s hand},{she prays}'),
(1050, 'CISSY CAFFREY', '{pulling Private Carr} Come on, you''re boosed. He insulted me but I forgive him. {shouting in his ear} I forgive him for insulting me. ', '  Come on, you''re boosed. He insulted me but I forgive him.   I forgive him for insulting me. ', '{pulling Private Carr},{shouting in his ear}'),
(1051, 'BLOOM', '{over Stephen''s shoulder} Yes, go. You see he''s incapable. ', '  Yes, go. You see he''s incapable. ', '{over Stephen''s shoulder}'),
(1052, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{breaks loose} I''ll insult him. {He rushes towards Stephen, fist outstretched, and strikes him in the face. Stephen totters, collapses, falls, stunned. He lies prone, his face to the sky, his hat rolling to the wall. Bloom follows and picks it up.} ', '  I''ll insult him.   ', '{breaks loose},{He rushes towards Stephen, fist outstretched, and strikes him in the face. Stephen totters, collapses, falls, stunned. He lies prone, his face to the sky, his hat rolling to the wall. Bloom follows and picks it up.}'),
(1053, 'MAJOR TWEEDY', '{loudly} Carbine in bucket! Cease fire! Salute! ', '  Carbine in bucket! Cease fire! Salute! ', '{loudly}'),
(1054, 'THE RETRIEVER', '{barking furiously} Ute ute ute ute ute ute ute ute. ', '  Ute ute ute ute ute ute ute ute. ', '{barking furiously}'),
(1055, 'THE CROWD', 'Let him up! Don''t strike him when he''s down! Air! Who? The soldier hit him. He''s a professor. Is he hurted? Don''t manhandle him! He''s fainted! ', 'Let him up! Don''t strike him when he''s down! Air! Who? The soldier hit him. He''s a professor. Is he hurted? Don''t manhandle him! He''s fainted! ', ''),
(1056, 'A HAG', 'What call had the redcoat to strike the gentleman and he under the influence. Let them go and fight the Boers! ', 'What call had the redcoat to strike the gentleman and he under the influence. Let them go and fight the Boers! ', ''),
(1057, 'THE BAWD', 'Listen to who''s talking! Hasn''t the soldier a right to go with his girl? He gave him the coward''s blow. {They grab at each other''s hair, claw at each other and spit.} ', 'Listen to who''s talking! Hasn''t the soldier a right to go with his girl? He gave him the coward''s blow.   ', '{They grab at each other''s hair, claw at each other and spit.}'),
(1058, 'THE RETRIEVER', '{barking} Wow wow wow. ', '  Wow wow wow. ', '{barking}'),
(1059, 'BLOOM', '{shoves them back, loudly} Get back, stand back! ', '  Get back, stand back! ', '{shoves them back, loudly}'),
(1060, 'PRIVATE COMPTON', '{tugging his comrade} Here. Bugger off, Harry. Here''s the cops! {Two raincaped watch, tall, stand in the group.} ', '  Here. Bugger off, Harry. Here''s the cops!   ', '{tugging his comrade},{Two raincaped watch, tall, stand in the group.}'),
(1061, 'FIRST WATCH', 'What''s wrong here? ', 'What''s wrong here? ', ''),
(1062, 'PRIVATE COMPTON', 'We were with this lady. And he insulted us. And assaulted my chum. {the retriever barks} Who owns the bleeding tyke? ', 'We were with this lady. And he insulted us. And assaulted my chum.   Who owns the bleeding tyke? ', '{the retriever barks}'),
(1063, 'CISSY CAFFREY', '{with expectation} Is he bleeding! ', '  Is he bleeding! ', '{with expectation}'),
(1064, 'A MAN', '{rising from his knees} No. Gone off. He''ll come to all right. ', '  No. Gone off. He''ll come to all right. ', '{rising from his knees}'),
(1065, 'BLOOM', '{glances sharply at the man} Leave him to me. I can easily ..... ', '  Leave him to me. I can easily ..... ', '{glances sharply at the man}'),
(1066, 'SECOND WATCH', 'Who are you? Do you know him? ', 'Who are you? Do you know him? ', ''),
(1067, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{lurches towards the watch} He insulted my lady friend. ', '  He insulted my lady friend. ', '{lurches towards the watch}'),
(1068, 'BLOOM', '{angrily} You hit him without provocation. I''m a witness. Constable, take his regimental number. ', '  You hit him without provocation. I''m a witness. Constable, take his regimental number. ', '{angrily}'),
(1069, 'SECOND WATCH', 'I don''t want your instructions in the discharge of my duty. ', 'I don''t want your instructions in the discharge of my duty. ', ''),
(1070, 'PRIVATE COMPTON', '{pulling his comrade} Here, bugger off Harry. Or Bennett''ll shove you in the lockup. ', '  Here, bugger off Harry. Or Bennett''ll shove you in the lockup. ', '{pulling his comrade}'),
(1071, 'PRIVATE CARR', '{staggering as he is pulled away} God fuck old Bennett. He''s a whitearsed bugger. I don''t give a shit for him. ', '  God fuck old Bennett. He''s a whitearsed bugger. I don''t give a shit for him. ', '{staggering as he is pulled away}'),
(1072, 'FIRST WATCH', '{takes out his notebook} What''s his name? ', '  What''s his name? ', '{takes out his notebook}'),
(1073, 'BLOOM', '{peering over the crowd} I just see a car there. If you give me a hand a second, sergeant.... ', '  I just see a car there. If you give me a hand a second, sergeant.... ', '{peering over the crowd}'),
(1074, 'FIRST WATCH', 'Name and address. {Corny Kelleker, weepers round his hat, a death wreath in his hand, appears among the bystanders.} ', 'Name and address.   ', '{Corny Kelleker, weepers round his hat, a death wreath in his hand, appears among the bystanders.}'),
(1075, 'BLOOM', '{quickly} O, the very man! {he whispers} Simon Dedalus'' son. A bit sprung. Get those policemen to move those loafers back. ', '  O, the very man!   Simon Dedalus'' son. A bit sprung. Get those policemen to move those loafers back. ', '{quickly},{he whispers}'),
(1076, 'SECOND WATCH', 'Night, Mr Kelleher. ', 'Night, Mr Kelleher. ', ''),
(1077, 'CORNY KELLEHER', '{to the watch, with drawling eye} That''s all right. I know him. Won a bit on the races. Gold cup. Throwaway. {he laughs} Twenty to one. Do you follow me? ', '  That''s all right. I know him. Won a bit on the races. Gold cup. Throwaway.   Twenty to one. Do you follow me? ', '{to the watch, with drawling eye},{he laughs}'),
(1078, 'FIRST WATCH', '{turns to the crowd} Here, what are you all gaping at? Move on out of that. {The crowd disperses slowly, muttering, down the lane.} ', '  Here, what are you all gaping at? Move on out of that.   ', '{turns to the crowd},{The crowd disperses slowly, muttering, down the lane.}'),
(1079, 'CORNY KELLEHER', 'Leave it to me, sergeant. That''ll be all right. {he laughs, shaking his head} We were often as bad ourselves, ay or worse. What? Eh, what? ', 'Leave it to me, sergeant. That''ll be all right.   We were often as bad ourselves, ay or worse. What? Eh, what? ', '{he laughs, shaking his head}'),
(1080, 'FIRST WATCH', '{laughs} I suppose so. ', '  I suppose so. ', '{laughs}'),
(1081, 'CORNY KELLEHER', '{nudges the second watch} Come and wipe your name off the slate. {he lilts, wagging his head} With my tooraloom tooraloom tooraloom tooraloom. What, eh, do you follow me? ', '  Come and wipe your name off the slate.   With my tooraloom tooraloom tooraloom tooraloom. What, eh, do you follow me? ', '{nudges the second watch},{he lilts, wagging his head}'),
(1082, 'SECOND WATCH', '{genially} Ah, sure we were too. ', '  Ah, sure we were too. ', '{genially}'),
(1083, 'CORNY KELLEHER', '{winking} Boys will be boys. I''ve a car round there. ', '  Boys will be boys. I''ve a car round there. ', '{winking}'),
(1084, 'SECOND WATCH', 'All right, Mr Kelleher. Good night. ', 'All right, Mr Kelleher. Good night. ', ''),
(1085, 'CORNY KELLEHER', 'I''ll see to that. ', 'I''ll see to that. ', ''),
(1086, 'BLOOM', '{shakes hands with both of the watch in turn} Thank you very much, gentlemen. Thank you. {he mumbles confidentially} We don''t want any scandal, you understand. Father is a wellknown highly respected citizen. Just a little wild oats, you understand. ', '  Thank you very much, gentlemen. Thank you.   We don''t want any scandal, you understand. Father is a wellknown highly respected citizen. Just a little wild oats, you understand. ', '{shakes hands with both of the watch in turn},{he mumbles confidentially}'),
(1087, 'FIRST WATCH', 'O. I understand, sir. ', 'O. I understand, sir. ', ''),
(1088, 'SECOND WATCH', 'That''s all right, sir. ', 'That''s all right, sir. ', ''),
(1089, 'FIRST WATCH', 'It was only in case of corporal injuries I''d have to report it at the station. ', 'It was only in case of corporal injuries I''d have to report it at the station. ', ''),
(1090, 'BLOOM', '{nods rapidly} Naturally. Quite right. Only your bounden duty. ', '  Naturally. Quite right. Only your bounden duty. ', '{nods rapidly}'),
(1091, 'SECOND WATCH', 'It''s our duty. ', 'It''s our duty. ', ''),
(1092, 'CORNY KELLEHER', 'Good night, men. ', 'Good night, men. ', ''),
(1093, 'THE WATCH', '{saluting together} Night, gentlemen. {They move off with slow heavy tread.} ', '  Night, gentlemen.   ', '{saluting together},{They move off with slow heavy tread.}'),
(1094, 'BLOOM', '{blows} Providential you came on the scene. You have a car...? ', '  Providential you came on the scene. You have a car...? ', '{blows}'),
(1095, 'CORNY KELLEHER', '{laughs, pointing his thumb over his right shoulder to the car brought up against the scaffolding} Two commercials that were standing fizz in Jammet''s. Like princes, faith. One of them lost two quid on the race. Drowning his grief. And were on for a go with the jolly girls. So I landed them up on Behan''s car and down to nighttown. ', '  Two commercials that were standing fizz in Jammet''s. Like princes, faith. One of them lost two quid on the race. Drowning his grief. And were on for a go with the jolly girls. So I landed them up on Behan''s car and down to nighttown. ', '{laughs, pointing his thumb over his right shoulder to the car brought up against the scaffolding}'),
(1096, 'BLOOM', 'I was just going home by Gardiner street when I happened to ... ', 'I was just going home by Gardiner street when I happened to ... ', ''),
(1097, 'CORNY KELLEHER', '{laughs} Sure they wanted me to join in with the mots. No, by God, says I. Not for old stagers like myself and yourself. {he laughs again and leers with lacklustre eye} Thanks be to God we have it in the house, what, eh, do you follow me? Hah, hah, hah! ', '  Sure they wanted me to join in with the mots. No, by God, says I. Not for old stagers like myself and yourself.   Thanks be to God we have it in the house, what, eh, do you follow me? Hah, hah, hah! ', '{laughs},{he laughs again and leers with lacklustre eye}'),
(1098, 'BLOOM', '{tries to laugh} He, he, he! Yes. Matter of fact I was just visiting an old friend of mine there, Virag, you don''t know him (poor fellow, he''s laid up for the past week) and we had a liquor together and I was just making my way home ...... {The horse neighs.} ', '  He, he, he! Yes. Matter of fact I was just visiting an old friend of mine there, Virag, you don''t know him (poor fellow, he''s laid up for the past week) and we had a liquor together and I was just making my way home ......   ', '{tries to laugh},{The horse neighs.}'),
(1099, 'THE HORSE', 'Hohohohohohoh! Hohohohome! ', 'Hohohohohohoh! Hohohohome! ', ''),
(1100, 'CORNY KELLEHER', 'Sure it was Behan our jarvey there that told me after we left the two commercials in Mrs Cohen''s and I told him to pull up and got off to see. {he laughs} Sober hearsedrivers a speciality. Will I give him a lift home? Where does he hang out? Somewhere in Cabra, what? ', 'Sure it was Behan our jarvey there that told me after we left the two commercials in Mrs Cohen''s and I told him to pull up and got off to see.   Sober hearsedrivers a speciality. Will I give him a lift home? Where does he hang out? Somewhere in Cabra, what? ', '{he laughs}'),
(1101, 'BLOOM', 'No, in Sandycove, I believe, from what he let drop. {Stephen, prone, breathes to the stars. Corny Kelleher, asquint, drawls at the horse. Bloom, in gloom, looms down.} ', 'No, in Sandycove, I believe, from what he let drop.   ', '{Stephen, prone, breathes to the stars. Corny Kelleher, asquint, drawls at the horse. Bloom, in gloom, looms down.}'),
(1102, 'CORNY KELLEHER', '{scratches his nape} Sandycove! {he bends down and calls to Stephen} Eh! {he calls again} Eh! He''s covered with shavings anyhow. Take care they didn''t lift anything off him. ', '  Sandycove!   Eh!   Eh! He''s covered with shavings anyhow. Take care they didn''t lift anything off him. ', '{scratches his nape},{he bends down and calls to Stephen},{he calls again}'),
(1103, 'BLOOM', 'No, no, no. I have his money and his hat here and stick. ', 'No, no, no. I have his money and his hat here and stick. ', ''),
(1104, 'CORNY KELLEHER', 'Ah, well, he''ll get over it. No bones broken. Well, I''ll shove along. {he laughs} I''ve a rendezvous in the morning. Burying the dead. Safe home! ', 'Ah, well, he''ll get over it. No bones broken. Well, I''ll shove along.   I''ve a rendezvous in the morning. Burying the dead. Safe home! ', '{he laughs}'),
(1105, 'THE HORSE', '{neighs} Hohohohohome. ', '  Hohohohohome. ', '{neighs}'),
(1106, 'BLOOM', 'Good night. I''ll just wait and take him along in a few ... {Corny Kelleher returns to the outside car and mounts it. The horseharness jingles.} ', 'Good night. I''ll just wait and take him along in a few ...   ', '{Corny Kelleher returns to the outside car and mounts it. The horseharness jingles.}'),
(1107, 'CORNY KELLEHER', '{from the car, standing} Night. ', '  Night. ', '{from the car, standing}'),
(1108, 'BLOOM', 'Night. {The jarvey chucks the reins and raises his whip encouragingly. The car and horse back slowly, awkwardly, and turn. Corny Kelleher on the sideseat sways his head to and fro in sign of mirth at Bloom''s plight. The jarvey joins in the mute pantomimic merriment nodding from the farther seat. Bloom shakes his head in mute mirthful reply. With thumb and palm Corny Kelleher reassures that the two bobbies will allow the sleep to continue for what else is to be done. With a slow nod Bloom conveys his gratitude as that is exactly what Stephen needs. The car jingles tooraloom round the corner of the tooraloom lane. Corny Kelleher again reassuralooms with his hand. Bloom with his hand assuralooms Corny Kelleher that he is reassuraloomtay. The tinkling hoofs and jingling harness grow fainter with their tooralooloo looloo lay. Bloom, holding in his hand Stephen''s hat, festooned with shavings, and ashplant, stands irresolute. Then he bends to him and shakes him by the shoulder.} ', 'Night.   ', '{The jarvey chucks the reins and raises his whip encouragingly. The car and horse back slowly, awkwardly, and turn. Corny Kelleher on the sideseat sways his head to and fro in sign of mirth at Bloom''s plight. The jarvey joins in the mute pantomimic merriment nodding from the farther seat. Bloom shakes his head in mute mirthful reply. With thumb and palm Corny Kelleher reassures that the two bobbies will allow the sleep to continue for what else is to be done. With a slow nod Bloom conveys his gratitude as that is exactly what Stephen needs. The car jingles tooraloom round the corner of the tooraloom lane. Corny Kelleher again reassuralooms with his hand. Bloom with his hand assuralooms Corny Kelleher that he is reassuraloomtay. The tinkling hoofs and jingling harness grow fainter with their tooralooloo looloo lay. Bloom, holding in his hand Stephen''s hat, festooned with shavings, and ashplant, stands irresolute. Then he bends to him and shakes him by the shoulder.}'),
(1109, 'BLOOM', 'Eh! Ho! {There is no answer. He bends again.} Mr Dedalus! {there is no answer} The name if you call. Somnambulist. {he bends again and hesitating, brings his mouth near the face of the prostrate form} Stephen! {There is no answer. He calls again.} Stephen! ', 'Eh! Ho!   Mr Dedalus!   The name if you call. Somnambulist.   Stephen!   Stephen! ', '{There is no answer. He bends again.},{there is no answer},{he bends again and hesitating, brings his mouth near the face of the prostrate form},{There is no answer. He calls again.}'),
(1110, 'STEPHEN', '{frowns} Who? Black panther. Vampire. {he sighs and stretches himself, then murmurs thickly with prolonged vowels} Who... drive... Fergus now And pierce ... wood''s woven shade ..? {He turns on his left side, sighing, doubling himself together.} ', '  Who? Black panther. Vampire.   Who... drive... Fergus now And pierce ... wood''s woven shade ..?   ', '{frowns},{he sighs and stretches himself, then murmurs thickly with prolonged vowels},{He turns on his left side, sighing, doubling himself together.}'),
(1111, 'BLOOM', 'Poetry. Well educated. Pity. {he bends again and undoes the buttons of Stephen''s waistcoat} To breathe. {he brushes the woodshavings from Stephen''s clothes with light hand and fingers} One pound seven. Not hurt anyhow. {he listens} What? ', 'Poetry. Well educated. Pity.   To breathe.   One pound seven. Not hurt anyhow.   What? ', '{he bends again and undoes the buttons of Stephen''s waistcoat},{he brushes the woodshavings from Stephen''s clothes with light hand and fingers},{he listens}'),
(1112, 'STEPHEN', '{murmurs} .... shadows ... the woods ... white breast... dim sea. {He stretches out his arms, sighs again and curls his body. Bloom, holding the hat and ashplant, stands erect. A dog barks in the distance. Bloom tightens and loosens his grip on the ashplant. He looks down on Stephen''s face and form.} ', '  .... shadows ... the woods ... white breast... dim sea.   ', '{murmurs},{He stretches out his arms, sighs again and curls his body. Bloom, holding the hat and ashplant, stands erect. A dog barks in the distance. Bloom tightens and loosens his grip on the ashplant. He looks down on Stephen''s face and form.}'),
(1113, 'BLOOM', '{communes with the night} Face reminds me of his poor mother. In the shady wood. The deep white breast. Ferguson, I think I caught. A girl. Some girl. Best thing could happen him. {he murmurs} ..... swear that I will always hail, ever conceal, never reveal, any part or parts, art or arts ...... {he murmurs.} ..... in the rough sands of the sea ... a cabletow''s length from the shore.... where the tide ebbs.... and flows ..... {Silent, thoughtful, alert he stands on guard, his fingers at his lips in the attitude of secret master. Against the dark wall a figure appears slowly, a fairy boy of eleven, a changeling, kidnapped, dressed in an Eton suit with glass shoes and a little bronze helmet, holding a book in his hand. He reads from right to left inaudibly, smiling, kissing the page.} ', '  Face reminds me of his poor mother. In the shady wood. The deep white breast. Ferguson, I think I caught. A girl. Some girl. Best thing could happen him.   ..... swear that I will always hail, ever conceal, never reveal, any part or parts, art or arts ......   ..... in the rough sands of the sea ... a cabletow''s length from the shore.... where the tide ebbs.... and flows .....   ', '{communes with the night},{he murmurs},{he murmurs.},{Silent, thoughtful, alert he stands on guard, his fingers at his lips in the attitude of secret master. Against the dark wall a figure appears slowly, a fairy boy of eleven, a changeling, kidnapped, dressed in an Eton suit with glass shoes and a little bronze helmet, holding a book in his hand. He reads from right to left inaudibly, smiling, kissing the page.}'),
(1114, 'BLOOM', '{wonderstruck, calls inaudibly} Rudy! ', '  Rudy! ', '{wonderstruck, calls inaudibly}'),
